animal.description:
Things did not work out for Theodore in his adopted home, so we welcomed him back to Rescue Row with open arms. Once a Rescue Row dog, always a Rescue Row dog. He is reactive and will bite, but when taught by every member of the family that this behavior in unacceptable, he has no issues. Theodore is looking for a small family with no young children that has had experience with a dog with similar issues and is willing to work on modifying his behavior. He is a 4 year old Shorkie (Shih Tzu/Yorkie Mix). Applications can be found at RescueRowInc.org

Theodore joined Rescue Row after a horrific attack by a larger dog. We are not sure how he did not sustain more serious injuries other than multiple surface wounds and a few punctures. On top of having wounds covering the backend of his body, he had mats everywhere preventing us from cleaning out his injuries properly. After being shaved down, we were able to clean out the wounds and assess the damage. He is in very good spirits and is resting and eating and drinking well. Theodore is a 3 year old Shorkie (Shitzu/Yorkie mix). Theo would do best in a home without children becuase sudden movements startle him. He also needs a home with another dog that he can play with and someone that can continue with his daily walks!

If you would like to adopt a dog from Rescue Row please fill out an application at https://form.jotform.com/91767055990166 

*Please check your junk email folder if you do not receive a response from a Rescue Row member within 48 hours.

*You must live within an hour of the DFW Metroplex because we do trial adoptions and require a homecheck

*Our adoption fees are as follows (paid by cash or a check made out to Rescue Row):

 Dogs 12 weeks-6 months old: $300 adoption fee

 Dogs 7 months and older: $275 adoption fee

Rescue Row is a 501(c)3 (non-profit) all volunteer dog rescue organization serving the DFW Metroplex. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations, and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances. We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs.

animal.description:
Meet Rosebud. This sweet bully girl was surrendered to the rescue when her owners moved to a community that did not allow "Pit Bulls." Rosebud's owners rescued her from a family who wasn't taking great care of her and keeping her outside. They loved and cared for her, and she was up to date on her vet care when we took her in...something we don't often see. They are an older couple, and the husband was dealing with health issues, so she wasn't getting the amount of daily exercise a young Bully girl needs to stay fit and healthy. She was also a bit spoiled from eating table scraps and has gotten a little thick around the middle.

Rosebud is currently in a SC foster home with one of our favorite families, Laine, Gary, and their pack of four pups. She is housetrained and crate trained, and does well with the other dogs. She prefers dogs who are more laid back, and her BFF is Mr. Charles, their dapper senior Boxer mix. She is not a fan of hyper pups who get in her face or try to take her toys, but do you blame her? Rosebud will hang out and sleep with the pack but is not super playful. That's just not her MO. She does like to fetch, but her favorite things include morning snuggles with Gary when she sneaks into bed, daily walks through the woods, chasing small critters while sniffing around the yard, and she loves sunbathing on the back deck.

Laine describes Rosebud as having a moderate energy level and some mild separation anxiety. Initially, she was anxious about being left alone and would bark/whine and try to get out of her crate. Now, she will whine but has earned free roam privileges in the home. She's respectful of things in the home and would do well with a good couch to nap on.

Rosebud is very friendly and loves to be near her people. She greets new people well and likes men and women equally. We feel a family with another mellow dog and a flexible work schedule would be the best fit for her. We also want to see Rosebud go to an active family who will make sure she gets daily walks and help her trim down to a healthier weight. Rosebud is still a young dog who is very connected to her people and has so much love to give.

This pretty Bully girl is ready to start her new life. Apply today!

Preference will be given to...

Families with another calm dog in the home

Owners with bully o
r large dog experience
Flexible schedule
NO CATS

BREED ESTIMATE: AmStaff (Bully) mix
GENDER: Male
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 62-64lbs
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 3 years
COAT TYPE: short
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/spayed/microchipped
LOCATION: Sterling, VA

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

animal.description:
Meet Bea! Born in May 2018, Bea is a miniature poodle mix seeking a special forever home. Bea’s foster mom describes her as a very shy girl who is still learning to be a real dog. After about a month in her foster home, her playful side really started to show with the other dogs but she is still learning to fully trust humans. Bea MUST have a home with other sweet tempered dogs who can engage in play with Bea. At least 1 other dog is required, but in Bea’s eyes, the more the merrier. She is currently fostered with other dogs of all sizes and cats but prefers the dogs with gentler souls in the home. Bea would do best in a home with gentle kids over 12. Her home will require a securely fenced yard as she still needs work on her leash skills and she likes to try to escape when left alone. Bea has bonded quickly with her foster parents but does get nervous when guests come over, so a quiet home would be best. Bea is not crate trained but does well with free roam of the house and is working on her potty training still because life inside a home seems to be a new experience for her. Bea’s forever family MUST be patient as it will take her weeks to adjust to a new family. After almost 3 months in her foster home she still startles very easily at loud noises, loud voices, etc. She does tend to try to hide and run away when left alone with new people. If she should get loose out an open door or through a fence, Bea will be difficult to catch again. ***Only dog homes, apartments, and families with children under 12 will NOT be considered. Applications for this sweet girl can be completed at www.mikeyschance.com.

No children under 5. 

Like all Mikey's Chance dogs, this dog will come to you from a foster home that has provided loving one-on-one attention, socialization and some basic training, as well as quality food and exercise. 

Applications can be found at www.mikeyschance.com and completed on a computer, tablet, and/or phone. Please note that adopters are not chosen on a first come, first served basis, but full consideration is given to the best fit for the dog AND the adopter. Applications can take up to 3 weeks to process. Application submission DOES NOT guarantee approval for adoption.

animal.description: Mayven is already ahead of the game with crate manners, place command, waiting at thresholds. She is also treadmill trained and walks well on a leash. If you are looking for a squishy face to cuddle, she is not your girl. Mayven's owner should be fluent on how to be a pack leader, and execute boundaries and structure. She will not be a dog park dog, but has learned how to play well with others in her current foster pack. Mayven is on the medium to low energy wise, and has learned how to connect with her human and follow their lead. She is very sweet, and enjoys well earned affection from her human. She is currently almost fully recovered from a skin infection, and is a chunky burrito. Mayven's future home will be able to reinforce boundaries, understand the importance of the use of "place", and will not be looking for a social pawn to take to Mutts or the dog park. She can be a bit pushy, and hardheaded. Her new home will also understand that it takes more than just love and affection to make a dog good. She will be a great addition to a well mannered dog pack that knows how to play and knows when to chill.

animal.description:
STELLA
Chihuahua
(DOB: 10/19/16)

Miss Stella was turned into the shelter because her owners said she had no quality of life being overweight with skin issues. DITR took her in and she’s already down from 11 lbs to 8.10 lbs. and on her way to being a healthy weight. She loves to walk! Exercise and a good diet does a body good. 

She is 4 years young and full of spunk.

Stella is sweet as sugar, but oddly has an issue with being picked up. She is getting better but it takes several tries of getting her to come close enough for her foster mom to pick her up!! She does love to be held or to sit in your lap! 
She loves the other dogs but is an attention hog and fusses at everyone for trying to sit with foster mom! Stella is totally house-trained and sleeps well in her calming bed all night without being crated. She is so precious!!

Stella is up-to-date on vaccines, spayed, microchipped and being maintained on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. 

Stella would do well in a home with possibly 1 other dog, but she would probably like to have a house all to herself!

This dog is currently being fostered as part of Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue. An application is required, along with a home visit and small adoption fee.  Applicants must be at least 21 years of age. **FENCED IN YARD REQUIRED**

Please visit us on our Facebook page for additional photos, give us a like while you're there! 
https://www.facebook.com/diamondsintheruffNC

All of our dogs are fostered in homes and are INDOOR dogs. We believe all dogs are family members and should be treated as valued members of the household. 

Please review our adoption guidelines for further information on adopting from Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue before submitting an application. www.DITRnc.com.

Name: Boxer
Breeds: Boxer/ Lab Mix 
Age: Adult
Gender: Male

Boxer is about the happiest dog you could meet in spite of all life has handed him. Found as a stray in Alabama, he had to have surgery on his hip to remove the femoral head (the "ball" part that fits in the hip socket).The good news of surgery is that he is all healed and that relieved his pain. He'll never be a long distance running partner but he loves his walks, playtime, and all those fun dog activities just like any other dog.Boxer is well mannered, housetrained on a schedule, and crates well. He is about 5 years old, 60 lbs so past those obnoxious puppy stages. He gets along great with other dogs, fine with cat, and loves kids. He is a total snuggle bug and loves to curl up with other dogs or people. Boxer is an easy dog to lose your heart to, he's just such a good boy. He was heartworm positive and has been treated,

Boxer was positive for heartworm disease and has recently been treated. More information on heartworm and treatment can be found here: http://headinghomek9rescue.com/Heartworm.pdf

Requirements: Home with yard space. 

Adoption Fee: $450 + tax. This includes neuter/spay, current vaccinations as age appropriate, heartworm/tick testing if appropriate, deworming, microchip, and current preventatives

Interested in adopting?  Fill out a preadopt application here: https://form.jotform.com/203104997748162

You can email fostersheadinghomek9@gmail.com with additional questions.

PLEASE READ THIS DESCRIPTION THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING FURTHER ABOUT THIS DOG.  IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN APPLYING TO ADOPT, PLEASE DO NOT REPLY VIA PETFINDER, INSTEAD GO TO  www.arizonapoodlerescue.org TO THE “Adopt Me” SECTION TO FIND OUR ONLINE APPLICATION.  WE WILL NOT ADOPT OUR DOGS OUT OF STATE.   PLEASE RESPECT OUR PROCESS AND OUR TIME AS WE ARE ALL VOLUNTEERS.  WE WILL BE GLAD TO ANSWER QUESTIONS ABOUT THIS DOG ONCE WE HAVE AN APPLICATION IN HAND.  PLEASE NO PHONE CALLS! 

 Mitchell is a 14-year-old black mini poodle mix and Snickers is a 7-year-old apricot terrier mix. They are a bonded pair whose owner passed away. The boys came to us rather obese, Mitchell was 25 lbs and Snickers 35 lbs. They have been working on their weight with a good diet and exercise. They have dropped quite a few pounds already. These two boys are rarely far apart. Snickers loves to play with other dogs and Mitchell will watch. Mitchell takes an OTC joint supplement and is still on a diet. Snickers wants to play and loves attention. He loves to follow his foster mom around He too is still on a diet. Snickers sheds some. The boys are working on their housebreaking, but do well if let out regularly.  They like to talk at dinner time, "hurry up with the food we are hungry". They enjoy sleeping together at night. Both boys are affectionate and social and happy to greet anyone. The boys need to go to a home together. There must already be a playful dog in the home. The boys get along great with people and other dogs.

There is an application and possible home visit or reference check prior to adoption.   Applications can be found on our website www.arizonapoodlerescue.org.   Click on the "Adopt Me" tab.    Snickers and Mitchell are being fostered in Phoenix.  Their adoption fee is $300 for the pair.

Arizona Poodle Rescue is an all volunteer non-profit organization.  We do not have a shelter.  Our dogs are currently being fostered in private homes generally located in the Phoenix and Tucson area.

animal.description: Boogie is a new arrival from his owner on November 14, 2020. He's a smallish 7-year-old fawn male who presented to us as shy and insecure, but apparently that all changes when he is confronted with another dog close by on leash. This was likely the root of the problem at his home: when he behaves aggressively toward another dog he may "redirect" his aggression at his owner or whoever is walking him. It seems that the simplest answer would be to make sure he gets plenty of exercise and stimulation at home in his yard, but perhaps that wasn't an option for his owners, and since he's somewhat overprotective of his home and owners anyway, it might preclude his success in a home with many visitors as well. On the plus side, Boogie is housebroken, and good with cats as well as kids, though once again we'd be concerned that kids typically have friends over and Bookie might or might not be ok with that. Ideally, especially at his early-senior age, he would be best paired with an older person or couple, perhaps retirees, who mostly keep their own company and enjoy having a lovable house dog to spend relaxing time with.

animal.description:
Lipton, 9 month old pup. 50 lbs. Needs a home with a yard.

Meet Lipton! This awesome boy will fill your days with joy. He is an affectionate dog who loves to play, run, hike and keep you company in whatever you are doing.

He is young pup and explores the world with his mouth so appropriate chewing toys must be available to him. He is a little timid on busy streets so we prefer to see him in a more quiet area rather than a busy city area. He gets along with all people but needs a bit more time to warm up to men.

Lipton can guard his toys and food which is something that needs work. We have him in boarding at the moment and working with a trainer so he can learn and improve. A committed owner who is willing to learn these skills and continue to work with him will be crucial to set him up for success. Since he also guards his food and toys from other dogs, Lipton will be best as an only dog. We prefer to see him in a home without kids.

Lipton knows basic commands. He sits very well. Learning to "stay" and "leave it." He plays very well with other dogs but can play hard which some dogs don't appreciate.

He walks well on a leash.

He is extremely loving and loves to give kisses. He is crate trained and will let you know if he needs to go potty.

Lipton needs an active family with a fenced backyard.

He is vaccinated, chipped and neutered. His adoption fee is $495.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
Please contact JoEllen (sagdinfo@aol.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Hope is a sweet 8-year-old Great Dane. She was abandoned by her previous owners at one of the most horrific kill shelters in the Rio Grande Valley. She was suffering from extreme malnutrition but has since achieved a healthy weight while in foster care. She now becomes very talkative if her foster mom is late with dinner! Hope lives in a foster home with other Great Danes and she interacts nicely with them - although she does not put up with any nonsense from the energetic younger Great Danes.
Hope did test positive for ehrlichia which is a bacteria infection caused by a tick bite and she completed a 30-day course of doxycycline.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for her entire life (up to 15+ years or more.)
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization.
Her adoption fee is $250. This includes her spay surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccination, Nobivac Intra-Trac 3 vaccination, Drontal Plus, Tri-Heart Plus Chewable Tablet, IDEXX SNAP 4Dx Plus Test, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.

Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved and you are traveling from out-of-town, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Hi Everyone, my name is Jameson aka Jamie and I will be 4 years old in January. I am ready for adoption after spending most of the year in foster care losing over 50lbs! I initially came to the rescue over 100 pounds with two torn knees and I am now down to 47 pounds and the vet thinks that the low 40s would be an ideal goal weight.

I likely have a little bit of basset hound in me which is why my ideal weight is in low 40s. I do need to stick to a strict diet of 600 calories a day until I reach my goal weight and then the calorie count can be readjusted if needed by the vet. I am prone to skin infections so I take an allergy supplement to help and the vet said baths with a medicated shampoo will also help keep infections at bay.

I had both of my knees repaired with a TPLO procedure which means I have two new knees with screws and plates which is pretty cool!! Both of my knees were torn due to being obese. The vet said there is no reason why the replaced knees shouldn’t last my entire life which is awesome news. And if it weren’t for the scars, you wouldn’t know my knees were replaced because I am very active and go for regular mile long walks several times a week.

I would do best in a home with no other dogs (unsure on cats) and no small children. I get along with my foster brothers most of the time but I have tendencies to resource guard items from other dogs. I am the most docile dog around humans. I am also doggy door trained but I do not like to be crated.

I love my foster home but I am looking forward to finding a forever home and hope you will want to meet me!

animal.description:
The best part of rescuing a dog is being able to provide a happy home for the imperfectly perfect souls of this world! To give the "underdog" a chance at a beautiful life. They sometimes come with the very best stories and make the very best companions. 

Let me introduce you to Beylita and her daugter, Lolita. They are two of the sweetest Chihuahua mixes- who weren't always that way. Due to their skin condition, they have run into not the nicest of people in the past and it took a while for these sweet girls to learn trust. They have been in an amazing foster home for the past few months learning what love is. What it is to always have full bellies, furry friends and hooman friends. Love is all around them now and they reciprocate it! These girls are now so amazing and loving, greeting you with bounces, tail wags, tongues out and bellies up! They look to be friends with everyone and every dog! A little timid at first but once they feel comfortable, it is all fun and love thereafter! They are fearless and love to be around dogs of all sizes, and are not afraid to give off a corrective growl toward another doggo when they feel uncomfortable. It never goes past that-- they just say "give me space" and trot along in the other direction, tail wagging! Now full of life and confidence, they can be yappy when excited but simmer down quickly. They are both crate and house trained and ready for a start to their new lives. Mom and daughter have lived all of their lives together and rely on eachother for comfort, so they will need to be adopted together. They are so tiny that two dogs is no different than having one-- double the love without taking up much more space! 

Beylita is estimated at 3 years of age and teeny tiny but a CHUNK, weighing in at 10 lbs! Her daughter is slightly bigger (also a chunky monkey), weighing in at approx 13 lbs. They both suffer from alopecia. We initially believed it was mange or some sort of skin infection but after medical treatment and different treatment approaches, we have learned that it is what it is. This is who they are and how they will always look-- nothing short of BEAUTIFUL! Convenia injections very temporarily make a difference. You will see some hair growth, but it quickly goes back to the adorable patchy look. It's very adorable, if you ask me! Beylita's chest and head are smooth like a baby's bottom! Their foster momma has also been working on nail trims and slowly cutting back at the overgrown nails they first started with-- huge progress!

If you are ready to fill your heart with so much love, please don't sleep on these two diamonds in the ruff! Apply here to bring them home https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/19764/generic or email cynthia@threelittlepittiesrescue.org if you have an application on file.

Their combined adoption fee is $900 and includes all vaccines (DHPP & booster, Bordatella, Rabies), spay microchip, multiple dewormings, heartworm treatment, flea and heartworm preventative with 2 month of heartworm preventative for each after adoption, a high quality nylon Martingale collar, a 30 day trial of pet insurance, and transport from TX to the PNW.

**APPLICATION REQUIRED FOR A RESPONSE**

animal.description:
UPDATE: ZOEY WAS ADOPTED BUT NOW IS AVAILABLE AGAIN

This poor girl, she just doesn't know how to act in every situation, definitely has some social issues, and always needs time to adjust. We thought we had found the perfect humans for her - they gave her tons of time to adjust and tried to make it work and did slow intros. She was VERY comfortable and loving with them, and they loved her too! Unfortunately she just couldn't get comfy with their little dog and ended up hurting her pretty badly - the other pup had to have stitches and will be ok, but now we are just scratching our heads as to what home will be the perfect fit for Zoey.

She is currently in a foster home with 5 other huskies and a cat all allowed to wander at will when humans are home, and after time to meet / greet / adjust with very close supervision, she is ok with all these animals. But she seems to have had a fair amount of issues in homes with other animals, sometimes seemingly at random.

She either needs a home with no other pets, or a very experienced owner who is able to monitor closely and allow her to adjust slowly, and have patience and hope she is a good fit with the other pets! She just seems to be pretty selective with others, and we can't really figure out what the determining factor is :( Total derpy, goofy, lovable sweetheart with humans though!

******* ORIGINAL BIO ********

Meet Zoey - we traced her history, and she used to be Princess, who was found as a stray in the summer of 2018 and adopted from the county shelter (https://www.facebook.com/.../a.21202.../2072127552838875/...) - she was listed as a project dog then, and unfortunately it doesn't seem much has changed. From what we have been able to figure out, she has likely been in AT LEAST 6 different homes by now. Her age estimate is 6-8, but she still has quite a lot of energy!

Her first night in a with us she was so skittish she barely allowed anyone to pet her and wanted to stay outside as long as she could - she acted petrified of the large dogs in the home. Next day, after receiving treats (she is SO food motivated!! Perfect for training!!), she warmed up a TON and has been wanting pets nonstop. Day 2 she was annoying the bigger dogs pretty nonstop barking at them and seeing how they would react to her and being pretty pesky overall - we are pretty sure this was just a total lack of socialization and no understanding of how you are supposed to make new friends! There is a small dog (11lbs) here as well and she has absolutely ignored him. A couple sniffs but hasn't barked at him once.

We are now onto Day 4 of Zoey with us, and she has had quite the transformation! Totally fine with the other big dogs, doesn't bark at them at all and wants nonstop love from humans - the problem is that with 6 dogs (and a cat) here she can't get the amount of attention and one-on-one training time she needs and deserves to thrive! She slept on the bedroom floor right next to the other dogs quietly through the night (though she does snore a tiny bit!) with no issues at all.  

We think her ideal home would be either as an only dog, with smaller dogs, or with one or two larger dogs coupled with an experienced owner who understands that her first few days anywhere are going to be an ADJUSTMENT! Once she opens up and warms up she is extremely sweet, but she desperately wants one place that is her own and after having been moved around so much, we think every time she is moved she is so stressed because she doesn't know where she belongs.

The original adopter who had her for 6 months stated that she lived in a home with a cat for that period of time, and that she had no aggression to the cat, but would chase here and there - not nonstop or relentlessly but that when the kitty ran, she would follow. If the cat swatted her she would accept correction.... there is a cat here that she has met and has had the same behavior. Runs up tail wagging to sniff curiously. Since the kitty is 13 and a grumpy old man, I would call her back every time and she would (with a little effort) pull herself away and come over with no aggression. Supervision still recommended!
She is going to need someone with patience to work with her! When she opens up she becomes extremely loving and snuggly and paws for pets even! But she clearly has some sort of trauma that is making it hard for her to trust instantly!

Please please let us know if you can help Zoey!

animal.description:
Emma is being foster in a loving home near Pennington, NJ. Her foster writes..

Emma
is adjusting well... I do think that she was never an indoor dog and everything thing inside is new to her.... She is very relaxed at home and seems to enjoy being in.... she is doing well in the crate but has figured out how to escape by pushing out the bottom layer, lol. We have kept her out of the crate for a few days for an hour or two and besides a few toilet paper rolls she has not chewed or disrupted much. You can see with each passing day she gets a little more comfortable but she is still very skittish when doing something for the first time. She has not had an accident inside and does her business on the leash within a few minutes of a brisk walk around the block.

We do notice that she much prefers the company of females. While she is daily warming up to me she absolutely LOVES Erin, she is MUCH more cautious around men. But everyday she is changing into a loving family pet.... but as you said when we started our foster she is adjusting well to a calm relaxed home

Emma and her sister, Ellie, were found as strays by a couple of men who were working in a wooded area. Ellie was fully pregnant and in need of some help if she were to be able to nurse her pups properly and Emma seemed a bit hesitant of the two men. When the two men returned to the job site the next day, they discovered that Ellie had delivered 9 puppies and that Emma seemed a bit more welcoming to them. They took the girls and puppies to their home and contacted their pastor, who then contacted SoCo Rescue.

When members of the SoCo team went to get Emma, Ellie and the pups, they discovered that Emma has also delivered two pups overnight. This came as a surprise to the two men as Emma hadn't looked pregnant the day before. SoCo Rescue took both moms and all 12 newborn pups into their care.

Emma initially was scared and apprehensive of our offers of help but quickly shed her fears of all that was new and uncertain to her. While she's still a little shy, she is now interacting very well with our staff. Her ideal home would be one without small children and a bit on the calmer side to give Emma the opportunity to adjust. We're positive that Emma will open up toher new family the same way she has with our staff.

Emma has been fully vetted, started on her monthly preventatives and de-wormed. Her recent heartworm test came back negative and she appears to be in excellent health despite her homeless ordeal. We don't think Emma has ever been an indoor dog or received much training so her adopter should be prepared to offer basic training to her.

If interested in adopting Emma, please submit an application at socorescue.com

FULLY SPONSORED ADOPTION
Meet our beautiful 4 year old girl Hope!

Hope came to Partners for Pets in January 2018. She's been in our care for just over 2 years now, and she's more than ready to find a home of her own. Will you help us find it??

If Hope had a Netflix account (or even knew what Netflix was) her go-to movie category would be "movies that feature strong female leads." Hope is an effervescent, intuitive and

playful girl who is looking for the right match in a playmate.

She needs a male playmate who is also very playful but will let her be in charge. Basically, she is the canine embodiment of every Beyonc song. She tends to be a little selective in a male partner, but honestly? Good for her. She knows her worth.

In terms of other pets, Hope gives cats a two thumbs down. (If she had thumbs, that is.) No small children, please.

If you're interested in adopting Hope and have a male dog who you'd like to introduce to her, fill out an application and we will be more than happy to schedule a meet and greet. This girl is something fiercely special to us, and we want to make sure it's the right fit.



Hope is spayed, current on all vaccinations, heartworm negative, dewormed and microchipped.

Adoption applications are available at
www.partnersforpetsil.org/
applications.

Adoptions are held at the O'Fallon, IL PetSmart every Saturday of the month from 11am-3:30pm and at the Glen Carbon, IL PetSmart every Sunday from 11am-3:30pm. We are also at Petco in Edwardsville Crossing on Sundays from 11:30-3:30 pm. The cats are only at Glen Carbon Petsmart. Please let us know if you are interested in a pet and we can arrange to have them meet you at one of the adoption events.

animal.description:
*** Smiley is available for adoption in our Foster to Adopt Program ***


Hi my name is Smiley! I'm about 2 years old and a medium size weighing about 40 lbs. I'm very sweet and I love to be touched and petted. There is nothing better than the love from my family!!

I have come to really enjoy taking walks! I am trying really hard not to be too nervous on the walks and like to stay near my person, so sometimes I try to stay right by my foster mom's legs while we are walking.

I'm really good about going potty outside and I've figured out how to tell them when I need to go. I sleep on a dog bed in my foster mom's room and I do fine with that but I am ok in my kennel if that's what you prefer as well. I really like being outside and I feel most comfortable in the fenced yard! I am a little anxious while riding in the car but with each trip I am getting much better!

My perfect family would be someone who is willing to be patient with me as I learn to understand all about this big new world. I have so much love inside me to give. I just know with love, patience and positive reinforcement I am going to blossom into a beautiful smiling flower!


FOSTER TO ADOPT:
Smiley just completed Heartworm treatment and is waiting for a negative test result which can take 2-9 months after treatment. During these months, she will need to make sure her heart rate is not elevated due to high energy play or exercise. Smiley is only available through the Foster to Adopt Program at this time. The commitment will be for an adoption but will be fostering until she is cleared with a negative Heartworm test result. All of the medical expenses will be paid for by the rescue while she is in a foster to adopt home. 



--------------------------------------------



All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Adoption Fee - $450

To apply for this pup, please submit an Adoption Application at http://warriordogrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

Please email info@prairiepaws.org to fill out an application and arrange an appointment to meet the pet. Want to get a head start on the application? Here's the link: DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/PPAS/Dog

Hadley is a young fun-loving, happy Retriever mix with an estimated DOB of 12/05/2019. He weighed 50 lbs at intake.  He came to us as a stray. Hadley just wants to say that sure girls just wanna have fun but he WANTS to have fun too! This goofy, life-loving, happy goofball just wants a family to call his own and teach him to be the best family member he longs to be. He wants to learn EVERYTHING! Helps that he is smart too. He LOVES toys, especially stuffed ones. He WILL chase cats and needs to be taught boundaries with the feline cuties. Hadley's adoption fee is $190 which includes a medical exam, sterilization surgery, age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormer, heartworm testing, and a microchip.

Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. As we get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

Our animals change daily, so please check our lists of adoptable dogs and adoptable cats frequently. Once you find an animal you’d like to adopt, the next steps are to complete an application and request a meet and greet with the foster. Make sure to be thorough and help us understand why you’re interested in that particular animal — and why your home is a great fit. Based on your answers we may even have a better fit for you.

All PPAS dogs are up to date on all of their vaccines (including rabies if age appropriate), and will be microchipped and registered in the adopter's name at the time of adoption. Adopters get a free consultation at an area vet partner within 14 days of adoption. Any dog that is six months of age or older will be tested for Heartworms and if found negative, will be kept on Heartworm prevention during their shelter stay, after the adoption it is up to the adopter to continue the highly recommended Heartworm preventative treatment. Also all PPAS shelter dogs are treated with a monthly topical flea/tick preventative and we ask that adopters continue that treatment as well.  All dogs and cats per state law are sterilized before they begin their new fabulous lives with their new families.

Adoption fees: Adoption fees must be paid in full at time of adoption – no partial payments are accepted. All major credit cards are accepted. Adoption fees vary. Please note if you live in the city of Ottawa a dog license fee must also be paid at time of adoption. Annual renewal of dog licenses is required between January 1st and February 15th.

Taking your animal home: The State of Kansas requires that all cats and dogs must be sterilized (spayed/neutered) before going to their new homes. In most cases animals will have already been sterilized before being placed on the adoption floor and you will be able to take your new companion home with you the day of adoption. However, if the animal is not yet sterilized, they will need to stay at the shelter and we will schedule the surgery on the next available date (usually within a week). We do request that all dogs go home with a collar/leash.

If you are interested in this pet, please either email Prairie Paws Animal Shelter at info@prairiepaws.org, for an application or visit our website @ prairiepaws.org for more information.

I enjoy seeing other dogs and so want to go to them to say "HI", so I tend to pull on my leash to get to them peacefully. I'm not at all dog aggressive-just being friendly. I don't have any know history living with other dogs, cats or children, and I would like to meet your family to see if we'd get along. I'll always have a big smile and be ready to love you when you return home to me. Best part of my day, in fact. I hope to meet you soon. Love, Kynda

Barbarella was rescued from a shelter. She was totally shut down and won't get up to walk. It was originally thought that she may have back leg issues but that is not the case she was just terrified and sick. It has taken some time but she is finally eating well and has gained a couple of pounds. She needs to be potty trained and leash trained. Her favorite thing to do is cuddle, so if you are looking for a great companion and have the love, patience and understanding for our Mastino Royalty Princess Barbarella please go to our website at www.mastinorescue.org and complete a Family Profile and a volunteer from our team will be in touch. Please be patient as we are extremely busy. Due to our insurance restrictions you must own you home, have a 6 foot privacy fence and no children under the age of 10 to be consider. Barbarella is currently in Missouri but transport to the perfect home can be arranged.

animal.description:
Have you met Wolfie?

5-year-old Wolfie was brought to the Lancaster Shelter with his 9-year-old sister Sofia after their owner passed away. They are very bonded, and we are looking to place them together in a home.

Shortly after becoming Frosted Faces on October 10th, Sofia and Wolfie went to live in a Foster home, and we've learned so much about what these two cuties are like in a home environment!

Wolfie weighs 25 lbs and follows boss Sofia. He is a happy-go-lucky guy and has the biggest heart. He has never met a stranger and loves it all, from kisses to cuddling and belly rubs. He is very well-behaved and loves to nap. Wolfie's limited vision does not stop him from enjoying anything in life. He mapped the house in about a day and confidently walks around without any problems. He adapted quickly and also follows his favorite human and Sofia for additional guidance as needed. Wolfie also has a skin issue which caused him to lose a massive amount of fur, but he has been receiving a medicated bath every few days and his fur has been growing back very quickly. His coat looks amazing now! His future family will need to continue to monitor this issue and possibly continue the medicated baths. The good news is that Wolfie is great at bath time and happily cooperates for some peanut butter. Wolfie's shedding is also very minimal.

Sofia and Wolfie's Foster Mom shared, "Sofia and Wolfie are a very special, bonded pair who love nothing more than to cuddle, nap, and follow their favorite human around the house. Sofia can typically be found burrowing under her favorite blanket on the couch with Wolfie following her along wherever she goes. They are typically mellow but do have an occasional burst of energy once or twice a day and comically wrestle with each other. Sofia does not seem to like large dogs but they both got along well with other small dogs at the Frosted Faces play yard. Wolfie does not appreciate it when other male dogs try to hump his sister Sofia, but who can blame him! They also enjoy taking short walks around the neighborhood and are both outgoing and friendly greet people of all ages.

Sofia and Wolfie are lovable couch potatoes and bring out the silly side in each other. They still have a fun, playful energy about them and are quite the comedy duo. Some people can be hesitant to adopt two dogs but when you meet them and see their relationship dynamic, you quickly realize why they should stay together and that having two dogs is not such a dramatic difference. They follow each other everywhere and do most things together, often simultaneously, so there is not much additional effort required. The biggest problem that you will encounter is deciding who to pet first! Sofia and Wolfie are the quintessential low energy lap dogs who are looking for a forever family with a comfy couch and two free hands for lots of petting."

Please see Sofia's profile for additional information about her!

Wolfie and Sofia are having a great time in their Foster home, but a Forever Family is what they want most of all! Apply to meet this amazing duo: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit during Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

animal.description:
IMPORTANT!!!   All adoptions are by appointment only going forward and are spaced 30 minutes apart. PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below).  You need to make sure that the animal in which you have an interest is still available and to set up an appointment to meet the specific animal.  Once you arrive at the shelter for your scheduled appointment, please follow the directions that you were given over the telephone. If you are running late for your appointment or will be unable to make your scheduled appointment time, notify staff immediately. This will enable them to schedule that time for another prospective adoptive family. If necessary, they will be able to reschedule your appointment to a more convenient time.  

ADOPTION RETURN: If you are looking for a happy dog, be sure to ask to meet SHIRLEY TEMPLE. This female bulldog/lab mix is a happy girl, as you can see from her photos. Getting outside even if it is just for a photo shoot is a big deal for shelter dogs.  She weighed 47 pounds at intake, but has been there for a while getting treated for a skin condition which has now cleared up. She was adopted at the end of December, at which time she was spayed. The family had other dogs and SHIRLEY was not able to successfully bond with the other dogs. It was determined that she might be best in a one dog home. She is available for adoption and can go home the same day because she has already been spayed. Please be sure to take an appropriate size dog crate with you in your car, as well as a dog leash, to your adoption appointment. Staff would like to ensure that both of you arrive home safely together. If you do have other dogs and want to consider her for an addition to your family, check with staff about how they can help to safely introduce her to your dogs at the shelter in a neutral environment first.  Call to schedule an adoption appointment now.

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. Please be sure to take the exact amount with you.

NOTE: All shelter fees are under review and may be changed or modified at any time without advance notice.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information.

Puppies under 12 months - $300

animal.description:
Meet Logan! Logan has had a rough go in his 6 short years of life. He was adopted through BDAR when he was just a wee little pup. Throughout his time with his first adopter, he developed severe skin issues. He became very itchy and started to lose his hair; specifically on his belly, neck, and behind. His past owner did their best to find a diagnosis and get him feeling better, but had to surrender him eventually due to financial constraints. He was slightly thin when he arrived too, but has been putting on weight with a special diet. He will have to be on this special diet until we find out more answers.
You can tell his body has not been kind to him. He looks older than 6 years old, but through it all he has not let that dull his sparkle. He is such a lover boy. He loves to cuddle and likes to be a lap dog if you let him. He is house trained and great in his kennel. He does really well with all the dogs in his foster home. Even the grumpy girl dog there likes him! He also does well with kitties.
Since he arrived back at BDAR, we have been in constant contact with a veterinarian about his diagnosis. We recently found he has a skin infection that was resistant to the antibiotics we were trying. He is now on new antibiotics and we should see improvement soon! He will likely be on this medication for 6-8 more weeks. After that time, Logan may not be out the woods completely and will require follow-up veterinary visits. Right now, he is on three types of medication and a special diet, all of which add up to a significant monthly expense. We are hopeful that the new antibiotic will do the trick and as time goes on, the other medications and maybe even the prescription diet can be eliminated. Anyone that adopts Logan can expect the need to have regular visits with their veterinarian for several months.
If you are interested in learning more about Logan and his needs or would just like to meet and adopt him, fill out an application today! You can also give us a call at 307-514-4024. We will be more than happy to answer any questions you may have about this sweet boy.If you are not viewing this adoption listing from our website at www.bdar.org, please go there to get more information, find our adoption application, or submit an inquiry. Our pets are listed for adoption on multiple pet listing sites and we do not always have control over whether those sites are regularly or accurately updated. We also cannot guarantee we will receive forms or inquiries submitted through these 3rd party sites. For questions, call us at 307-514-4024. 2/2/21 4:51 PM

animal.description:
Why Choose Me?

I remembered Mia as soon as I saw her, and she remembered me. She came bounding out of the back of her kennel and was thrilled to see an old friend. Mia had been adopted from ACCAS earlier this year, and she was the same sweet dog I remembered. She sat next to me on the picnic table enjoying pets and being close. Her coat was soft and well-cared for. 

When I got home, I looked up her old bio and read that she had originally been nervous and always going to the gate like she was ready to go home. It also said that she could climb fences. Mia wasn’t nervous today, but after we visited for a while, she did go to the gate and stand and look at me like she was saying it was time for her to go home. 

I bet Mia is a wonderful companion. Hopefully, she’ll be reunited with her owner, but if not, she’ll bond with a new family. I don’t know if she can still climb a fence but being inside with her loved ones would probably suit Mia just fine.

If you are interested in fostering, adopting, or rescuing Mia, call 706-613-3540 to discuss options with staff.

You can read more about this dog and check out additional photos here: https://athenspets.net/Adoptables/54673-mia/ OR check out our urgent dogs (http://tinyurl.com/Athenspets-FB-URGENT-Dogs) on Facebook!

This dog is currently at Athens-Clarke County Animal Control, located at 125 Buddy Christian Way, Athens, GA. For the most timely information on hours, location, availability and how to adopt, call the shelter any day from 10am-4pm at 706-613-3540 or go to https://www.athensclarkecounty.com/133/Animal-Control.

animal.description: Choco came to us from an upstate animal shelter after his owners surrendered him because they had trouble confining him. Apparently he was typically tied up, but when the family's kids came home from school they untied him and left gates and doors open. He went to a neighbor's house and initiated fence-fighting with the three resident Jack Russell Terriers. There was difficulty with the animal control officers determining specifics about Choco because of a language barrier. From what was learned, Choco can be quite protective of his home, owners and car, even jumping out of a car window after perceiving a threat. He's reactive on leash to other dogs but appears to be able to live with compatible dogs, and he was good with the kids he lived with. If we place him with kids, they should be old enough to responsibly keep gates and doors closed since Choco has shown he'll dash out and be territorial about his home. It was also noted that he had killed a cat. He's about 2 years old.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Introducing CC! She's a bully mix that will turn 5 years old in February. She is 64 pounds of loves, cuddles and kisses. CC loves taking walks and would be a fantastic running partner. Her leash manners need some fine tuning. She is highly motivated by treats and quickly picks up on routines and wants to learn new skills. CC would be a fantastic fit for an active family. She adores people, but sometimes forgets about her size and can get overexcited. CC would also do best as an only dog. CC knows basic obedience commands like sit and wait. Chasing after balls, loving on her "baby" and playing tug are just a few ways she likes to spend her days. CC is crate trained. If she doesn't win you over by just her sweet nature, she certainly will with her "singing" skills where she can say "I love you".

All our dogs require secure VISIBLE fencing. Height dependent upon the dog.

All current pets in adoptive home must be spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Adopter must be at least 21 years of age.

animal.description:
Milton is a recent rescue from HCAS looking for a forever home. He went straight in to training to address some behavior/socialization issues he had not yet learned but has done very well. He is fully vetted and chipped HW+ but has started a slow kill regimen. 

This is the trainers take on Milton......
Milton likes the company of the humans but he'll tell you when his not in the mood, so I'd say no small children. He does well with other dogs he's selective with who he plays with, I think he likes playful dogs, so young dogs will be ok too. He might need a confident owner, someone with alpha personality, someone that can give him Boundaries and not someone that thinks he's going to be his baby, at that point Milton will start becoming dominant again and his old habits will emerge. He's a dog that needs to understand his place in the house. As long as that is clear everything will be fine. He knows better, he listens and respond very well to commands so as long as the adopter uses the training he knows and treats him as a dog and not a baby things will be fine.

animal.description:
Daisy was surrendered to PNW Cattle Dog Rescue in August from a family in Texas. They had gotten her from another family that kept her in a 10' x 10' kennel for the first 8 months of her life. With her people, Daisy is sweet, affectionate and eager to please. She needs an adopter who is ready for a high-drive cattle dog. She is very smart and wants to engage with her people. She'll start predicting your next action if you're not paying attention! She'd love to do agility or other dog sports. Around the house she often acts before she thinks so she needs practice with impulse control and basic obedience.

Daisy has struggled with the transition to life in the Northwest. She's reactive to moving vehicles, bikes, skateboards and other animals. We recommend an adoptive home without other animals. In the foster home, Daisy has will guard or steal food and toys from other dogs if given the opportunity. She'd need quite a bit of management in a multi-dog home til she feels more secure with family and routine. She has gone after cats and chickens in previous living situations, so we don't recommend an adoptive home with small animals. Given her current level of reactivity and her training needs, we will not place her in a home with small kids. 

Daisy loves fetch with frisbee or ball. She's very athletic and LOVES playing in water! She loves trail running with her foster dad. She likes dog toys and will happily entertain herself if there's nothing else to do. She's content napping on couch when things are mellow around the house. After a transition to a new living situation, Daisy initially shows mild separation anxiety when crated or alone (barking, whining). But once she's settled in the new environment and routine, she's comfortable alone. She loves Nylabones and chew toys.

In Jan 2021, Daisy is in board & train with Kay Fontaine of The Mindful Mutt in Seattle, WA. Her adoptive home will need to be dedicated to on-going basic obedience training, impulse control and a heavy emphasis on helping reduce her reactivity. Daisy will be available for meet & greets with potential adopters during this time! If you're interested in meeting Daisy, please fill out an adoption application on our website: pnwcdr.org/adopt 

Daisy is 1.5 years old, spayed, microchipped and has received age-appropriate core vaccines. Daisy's adoption fee is $330. Please note: We do not do DNA testing on our foster dogs. The breed description is our best guess based on the dog’s appearance, mother’s appearance, paperwork, etc. 

ADOPTION PROCESS: 
- Adoption Application
- Phone Convo 
- Meet & Greet

animal.description:
THANOS NEEDS A FOSTER OR LOVING FOREVER HOME!!!
Fosters make it possible for Dogs XL to save and care for homeless and abandoned dogs! To learn about fostering dogs like Thanos, please contact us at http://www.dogsxlrescue.org/volunteer/foster

Name: Thanos

Breed: Great Dane

Approximate Age: 11 months 

Approximate Weight: 110 pounds

Currently Living at: Local foster home



Meet Thanos! Thanos is a big, rambunctious boy with a lot of puppy energy and a heart as big as his body! Thanos is an absolute love with his people, but he can be wary of strangers so he needs a quiet home without a lot of people coming and going and a family who’s willing to help socialize him gradually so he learns that new humans = new friends! Thanos has not had much formal training and sadly, he's been bounced around a bit because of his size and energy, so Thanos is looking for a committed forever family who will help him learn his manners and can handle a bit of a bull in a china shop! Since Thanos is just a 110 pound puppy, he is looking for an adopter with large/XL dog experience who knows how to handle an overgrown pony who wants to sit in your lap and lean against your leg at all times. Thanos does well with other large dogs and would love a dog buddy to wrestle and play with! Though he is a sweet and affectionate guy, Thanos is probably best suited to an adults only home and is not well-suited to a family with young children. With some patient, consistent training, Thanos is sure to be the best ever companion for his new family! Apply today to meet Thanos! 


Thanos needs a foster or a loving forever home to lavish love and attention on him. Please open your heart and home to Thanos!


The adoption fee for this dog is $300, which includes the cost of heartworm treatment and routine vetting, including vaccinations and spay/neuter.

 

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out the application online at http://www.dogsxlrescue.org/adopt/adoption-questionnaire

 

Thank you for considering adoption and helping to save a life!


Please visit us online at www.DogsXLRescue.org

animal.description:
90% house trained, crate trained, great with other dogs, not sure about cats, shy with people. Calm for a Husky mix which is great thing for him and his family to be.

Luca will put a smile on your face.  He is still a young dog at maybe just a year old, and he wants what every dog or cat wants: a safe, friendly, warm home to call his own.  He is waiting for the right family.

He is a sensitive boy who needs a moment to learn that you are a friend.  Once he's feeling safe and secure in a loving home setting, his adorable personality will shine.

Luca will benefit from an adopter who appreciates his intelligence, diligence, and loyalty all of which he will show off through basic obedience training such as learning how to walk on a leash and basic commands.

He can live with another dogs similar in size and personality (mellow, aware).

Luca is looking to join a family with an experienced adopter and kids 14-and-up.

Applications are online at karmicrescue.org

What breed is my dog? Please remember we do not complete DNA tests on our rescued pups. If we do not know who the mom or dad is for sure, we guess; we use Bing Visual Search. And, we look at their paws, ears, snout, coloring, and body build. So often, we are not spot on. Mutts are usually more healthy than not. And, remember too that even if you know the supposed dominant breed in your new puppy or adult dog, it does not mean that those particular genes will dominate your dog's personality.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name:Honeymaren
DOB:12/12/2011
Weight:12
Adoption Fee: $125

This animal is part of our "Seniors for Seniors" program where we offer senior animals adopters an opportunity to adopt a pet at a discounted fee.

Honeymaren is very scared as she can from a hoarding situation. The foster has not been able to touch her but she follows her foster mom everywhere. She also wants to bolt so she has not even been outside she uses pads so that's good. The foster is currently just letting her do her thing and when she's ready she's hoping she will be a loving dog and that her resident dogs will show her the way. Honeymaren will need a very patient home and would do best with someone who has shy dog experience. She will need a very quite home as she is scared of noises. She does bark at noises so probably no apartments or shared wall living.

At her dental cleaning the vet did hear a heart murmur but she seems to be a healthy girl.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals!

All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs).

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

We greatly appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort, and safety of a home and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if needed), etc. If you are interested please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

PLEASE NOTE: GPMR communicates primarily by email. If you have any questions regarding one of our Mastiffs, please read their bio and if you still have questions- drop us an email at info@greatplainsmastiffrescue.org . If you have questions about our adoption procedures, please go to our Pages of Interest on the left hand column under 'Adoption Info.' We answer email inquiries almost immediately-usually always within a few hours and phone calls are returned with 24-36 hours.

GPMR does not have a shelter. All of our dogs are kept in loving foster homes. We must have a completed adoption
application on file before meeting any of our mastiffs.

GPMR adopts to the states of Oklahoma, Texas, Kansas, Arkansas, Missouri, Louisiana and parts of Colorado.
!!!Any mastiffs being adopted out of the state of Oklahoma require a health certificate to be paid for by the adopter!!!

Meet Sly! He came into GPMR with several of his relatives after being rescued by a local SPCA from a neglect situation. The breeder of these dogs was not providing adequate food or any vet care and turned them over to the SPCA. They were extremely underweight when they arrived at the SPCA. All of these dogs lived together and but were not socialized at all outside the home, and so in new situations they are very fearful. In their foster homes, they are doing great and do not show many signs of fear at all. We are working on leash training as only one of the dogs knew how to walk on a leash, the rest just dropped to the ground and wouldn't move. All of the dogs had fleas, intestinal parasites, and varying degrees of skin/ear/eye infections. The SPCA did an amazing job getting them started on the road to good health!Sly is 2 years old. He was one of the less fearful dogs in this group but while he has adjusted great to his foster family, he is very scared in new situations. He also is learning the comforts of sleeping on the couch and in bed with his foster mom. Sly is a velcro Mastiff for sure. When we first tried crating him, he panicked and immediately tried to break out of the crate. It's not uncommon for these guys to have some separation anxiety like this going through the rehoming process. We is adjusted to the crate now and does well in there, primarily used when his foster family leaves the home otherwise he will chew stuff up. Sly's adoptive family will need to be patient with him through this adjustment. He should have another dog as a canine companion which should help. He would love to have a family who is home most of the day. He is also good with cats! Sly lives with teenagers and does just fine with them. Since we don't have any history of him with young kids, a home with older kids 12+ would be best. He would do best with someone who is home part of the day.Sly is being fostered in Edmond, OK.Save a Mastiff...Adopt, Foster, Volunteer!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.JAN 2021 UPDATE: Hi all! Jana here. I'm a sweet southern gal we loves life to the fullest. My foster mom says I'm a muscle bound ball of energy. I can run, jump & would love to play all day long. My fur foster brother is nice but a bit on the lazy side. He also can have a bad attitude. When meeting another dog, I need time. I do not know how to control myself so very, very slow intros are a must. I'm very well behaved. I know sit, shake, wait, come. I'm part hound so when my nose is going I'm busy. Lol. I love people so much. I get really excited when I see my people. I jump & jump some more. I might be too much for toddlers. I will need someone who will keep me in line or I will take over the household. ______________________________________________From the foster mom: Jana will need someone who can set boundaries and work on her obedience skills. She had too much freedom in her past home and took advantage of the situation. Jans is improving daily and is very smart. She wants to learn and please her people. No young children in the home until she learns more indoor manners. Jana loves to play and after appropriate introductions, she can have lots of fun chasing and playing with other dogs. Jana does have a prey drive for outside critters so probably not good with cats.In Jana's own words: 'My foster mommy took me to work today. It was fun & very exhausting. I sat waiting to be shown what to do. Mommy brought me to 'my station'. It had a comfy place to lay down, toys, stuff to chew on. I'm thinking jack pot! Then I heard noises from the ceiling. I knew mommy didn't hear them so I let her know something was up. She told me it was a karate class? So then I let them know that I was down below & they were disturbing us. I also greated people & asked them if they really truly liked what they were eating. It was the best day.'Jana is brand new to RCBR and we are just learning about her. A few things we do know already is -- she has her full tail and knows how to use it and she is so well behaved and will sit & wait before going outside or through a gate. Jana can be picky with other dogs. Might be best as an only pet, but with time could get along with the right dog. Stay tuned for more details! Current foster home location is Minnesota. Click here to watch a video of Jana.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet our sweet and snuggly Diamond, Simba!

Simba was pulled from a local shelter where he was an owner surrender with a life threatening injury. He had surgery and received the care he needed, but then it was discovered he was heart-worm positive.

With a face like that - we knew we had to save him! One of our volunteers stepped up to foster him and could tell immediately what a sweet boy he is. He's a 65lb, goofy, lap dog!

Simba is VERY treat motivated! He knows his basic commands - sit, stay, down and rollover :) Even though he is a smart cookie and knows these commands, he needs to work on not stealing pizza off the counter.

Because Simba is currently going through heart-worm treatment, he can only go to a home that will get him through this treatment. He does get along with other dogs with slow introductions, but because he wants to play he will need to be kept separate and calm. He also gets scared / startled easily so would do best in a home without a lot of traffic coming in and out and needs to be slowly introduced to new people.

Please fill out an application today to meet this handsome boy named Simba!

**Follow Simba's journey on Instagram at @snuggly_simba

Adoption donation includes Spay/Neuter, UTD on Vaccinations, deworming, and flea treatment.

animal.description:
Fred is a 3 year old neutered male feist mix who weighs 26 lbs. Fred was rescued from a property with many other dogs. Sadly, he was never given the care and attention he deserved and is understandably shy in new situations as a result. Living in a home is totally new to this sweet guy, so he is looking for a patient family that will teach him about the finer things in life. Fred warmed up to his foster mom quickly and now greets her with lots of tail wags and excitement. He is as loyal as they come and loves to follow her around. Fred is looking for a home with a fenced-in yard, as he is still learning how to walk on a leash. Fred seems to be wary of dogs that are bigger than him, so he needs a home without medium or large dog. Fred has done well with the respectful children he's met that understand to give him space as he settles in. Once he settles in, Fred is a puppy at heart and is very playful. He is good with cats, and he has been making progress with housebreaking and crate-training. We are so excited to watch Fred continue to blossom in a forever home. Could that be yours?

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization, so we do not have a facility to visit. Please read our FAQs to learn more: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq
Follow us on Facebook for foster updates and a full list of our adoptable pets: https://www.facebook.com/all4pawsrescue/

animal.description:
Breed: German Shepherd mix
Sex: Male
DOB: ~11/24/2016
Weight: 84.2 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Happy, Playful, Affectionate, Social, Energetic
History: Transferred from another shelter. 
Good With: Dogs, Kids 8+ years
Fence Requirements: Preferred
Ideal Home: Active home! No apartments.
Special Info: Stewie is OBSESSED with tennis balls!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Meet Bella Jae! Bella Jae is about two years old and is a Pitbull and Dalmatian mix. Bella Jae is the happiest dog. She's always so excited to greet people and doesn't know a stranger. She is a higher energy dog and would love to find a family that will take her on lots of walks. Bella does not have a lot of social skills when it comes to other dogs. She wants to be friends but isn't quite sure how to do that, and can be a bit dominating when trying to play. We are unsure how Bella Jae would do with cats but when she saw them through a window she was wiggly and seemed like she wanted to play.

All dogs are $100 which includes having them spayed/neutered, current on vaccines (age appropriate) and microchipped.

While the shelter is currently closed due to COVID-19, we are setting appointments for adoptions or fosters. Please call 812-376-2505 or email animalcareservices@columbus.in.gov.
