animal.description:
Thank you for considering a homeless/rescue dog, it does not matter where dogs are from what matters is where they will live the rest of their life. 

If you are looking for a walking and hiking partner Coco is the girl for you.  She loves to walk and explore the different surroundings in the woods.  Her daily walking route is a rural path in the woods, her foster home is in a rural area away from the city.  Coco walks very well on a long lead.  When she sees her walking harness she becomes very excited.

Coco is very sweet with beautiful honey brown eyes that invite you in she has a face that no one can resist, her red nose is always looking for a treat.  She knows to sit for her treat and food.  After relieving herself she runs back for her treat, she’s very smart, she’s the full package, good nature, good temperament and an amazing personality; she is loving and loyal great companion and dear friend she will bring much affection and love to a good family. 

It is difficult to identify mixed breed dogs without proper knowledge of ancestry; a guess assessment of breed and age has been made, Chocolate Labrador mix, keep in mind Coco was a rescue dog once a stray but it is a known fact that she is certainly a true gem and a keeper.  Coco is approximately 1 1/2 years old, 65 pounds of happiness, she loves life, loves everyone, always ready to play and ALWAYS ready for a snack. 

Coco is looking for a family who will open their home and invite her in to join their family, she only wants to belong.  Coco was owner surrendered, her family decided to surrender her to Paws & Claws Rescue the family was not active and Coco needs an active family and Coco was considered an added expense.  She had an unhappy beginning, she’s 2 years old and has given birth to 5 puppies.  Her life began on a chain she shows her appreciation giving wet messy kisses.  She has left her miserable, depressing life behind.   Rescue dogs form a lifelong bond with their families and are forever grateful for their new happy family and life.  

Activity level:        High energy
Favorite toy:         Rubber Kong toy stuffed with peanut butter
Temperament:      Friendly temperament/sociable loves everyone.
Personality:           Awesome

Now, her dream is having a good home with lots of toys of her own, bed, a home with a family that will shower her with love and attention, please open your heart and home give Coco a chance to prove her love”. She is looking ahead waiting for a forever home where she can hang her leash and call “Home, Sweet Home”.  Coco is potty trained she sleeps in her large wire crate at night, sleeps all night.    

On nice weather days Coco spends her days basking in the sun in a fenced yard she enjoys napping in her doghouse.  Her activity level is high energy still very much a puppy herself.  She has a lovely personality she loves children, older children are recommended she is a big dog and rambunctious too active for small children/toddlers.  

Coco is up-to-date on all her vaccinations and has been spayed.  Her adoption donation of $395.00 includes all her expenses and vetting.  Please email Delia Coco’s foster mom for an application at rubsch@sbcglobal.net and include your phone number.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Catahoula Mix|2 yrs|45 lbs.|$400.00Sinatra is a playful and energetic 2-year-old, 45-pound Cataloua mix who is ready for his family to come fly with him.

Sinatra flies around the yard or through the woods at speeds that make you wonder if he has wings. He enjoys playing with other dogs as they catch his tail winds trying to catch up in a game of chase. Sinatra is a smart boy who always is working, calculating his altitude and path through sniffing the ground and putting his nose to the wind to determine flight conditions. When he does take time off, this boy enjoys the comfort of a pillow and blanket with his head resting on his human's lap.

Sinatra is happy to work with other canines as flight attendants to his pilot. However, he has not yet been around with cats or children, so we are unsure whether they would make a good crew.

Sinatra is an energetic pup looking for a home filled with ample activity, a sense of purpose and lots of love. Once Sinatra finds his family, he looks forward to holding them near to his heart, and who knows, angels may cheer because he and his family are together. If you are interested in meeting Sinatra, fill out your flight plan (application) at https://rescuecrew.org/adopt-animal-in-need/#adoptionapplication

The adoption fee covers the cost of the animal's spay/neuter surgery, microchipping, FIV/FeLK testing (for cats) or Heartworm Testing (for dogs), deworming and all core age appropriate vaccinations. For the most complete information regarding this animal, and all of our adoptable pets, please ensure you are visiting our website directly at www.RescueCrew.org. You can also access the necessary online adoption application here as well. Thank you.

animal.description:
Lucy is a 2 yo terrier mix who LOVES to play.  She's all of 35lbs and QUEEN of the head-tilt.  She is one spunky girl, so an active family, who can spend some time playing fetch with her, would be ideal.  Lucy is part bunny, so a secure fenced yard (at least 6ft tall) is a must for this bouncy, happy girl.  Lucy is all about chew toys and stuffies!  When she gets her mittens on a stuffie, she goes into full puppy mode.   As active as Lucy is, she absolutely adores cuddling up to her people.  Lucy=Snuggle Bug

Lucy was found by a very kind woman, wandering the streets of Birmingham, with painful neck lacerations from having been tied out.  Because of her past, Lucy's neck is sensetive (but completely healed) to collars and slip-leads, and she requires a harness.  She is leash-reactive, so an expereinced adopter is needed.  We recommend she be the dog in the home, as her days of being tethered have resulted in her being very nervous around other dogs, especially when she's on-leash.  She seems to be disinterested in cats.   

If you're interested in meeting sweet Lucy, please submit an application on our website!

http://mustlovepawsrescue.com/home

animal.description:
Giselle is a stunning girl who is very sweet and clearly adorable. She loves to cuddle almost as much as she loves to PLAY! She is good with other dogs and fine with cats. She is a big-time resource guarder and will get fussy over toys she sees as hers in a home with other dogs. She would do best in a home where she is her person's one-and-only. She takes some time to decompress in a new home and really thrives when there is structure and a routine. If you show her she can rely on you to keep her safe, she will be your best friend and show you undivided devotion like only a hound dog can.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out an application. We do allow out of state adoptions and any transport costs are at the expense of the adopter. If you have further questions about this dog, please email us at ccradopt@gmail.com and someone will be in touch as soon as possible.

Please understand that we are an all volunteer group and we have jobs outside of this organization. We do our best to provide quick responses but occasionally they are a little slower. If you do not receive a response in 48 hours, please resend to make sure it's received.

animal.description:
Rockwell- Male/Neutered , American Bulldog Mix  Color: Red & Tan 4 -5 years old 94 lbs.
ID# D-39901
***Heartworm Positive***

Rockwell was found as a stray in another city and brought to the shelter after being unclaimed. He is a handsome American Bulldog mix with maybe Mastiff? He's a very large guy, very well mannered, and housebroken. He's pretty laid back, likes to lounge around, would make a fantastic inside house companion. He gets a little nervous with loud noises, etc, so we feel it be best, if kids are in the home, they be older such as 12 or older and preferably a quieter home. A secured fenced yard would be needed for exercise and bathroom breaks, the rest of the time, he must be indoors.

Rockwell is current on basic vaccinations including Bordetella, been dewormed and is microchipped. He has tested POSITIVE for Heartworms. He will need to be on Heartworm prevention for the rest of his life and stay as mostly an indoor dog. He has been started on the slow kill medications for Heartworm at the time of his neuter.

Rockwell has now been neutered as of  12/15/20 and has received his required Rabies vaccination. 

For more information, please contact the City of Corsicana Animal Shelter at (903) 654-4928. The shelter is open Mon, Tues, Thurs and Fri from 12:00pm - 6:00pm and on Sat from 12:00pm - 4:00pm.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 08/01/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Lavender and her 3 babies were seized as part of a hoarding case. Carolina Poodle Rescue partnered with a local shelter to help her and her babies.
Foster location: Foster Home in Raleigh, NC
Special Needs? Lavendar was spayed and had a dental on 9/25/20. Her days of making babies are over and she's ready for her forever home. Lavender requires an owner experienced with chihuahuas.
Weight: 8.5 lbs
Height: 9 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No, but she would love one

What kind of home would be best for me? Lavendar is a shy but very loving girl. She needs an experienced dog owner that has patience to earn Lavendar's trust. Once she trusts you, she is yours! Lavender is not for a first time dog owner. She is not for a home with children. This mama is looking for a quiet home where she will be the lap princess. Lavender needs another dog in the home. As she has come out of her shell she seeks out her foster siblings and loves to play and run with them. Other dogs help her build confidence.

Lavendar cannot live in an apartment or any other dwelling with shared walls. Her voice is simply too much. It will take Lavendar at least 5 days to settle into her forever home. For the first 5 days she will be nervous, anxious, and may even show her teeth. Change is very hard for this girl. Patience and calm are required for a successful adoption.

What is my personality like? Lavender arrived in rescue as a very shy but calm mama with 3 very young babies. Given the age of her babies she was moved to a foster home immediately. Lavender was the best mom!! She was so nurturing and sweet to her babies. Now that they've found their forever home, it is this mama's turn.

Lavendar has really come out of her shell in her foster home. She loves to sleep in the bed, way down under the covers. She loves to play with toys. She loves to run zoomies in the yard with her foster siblings. She is incredibly food motivated and will work for treats. Lavendar wants to be where people are. Though she can be skittish, her heart is big and gentle and she loves with every ounce of it.

Lavendar has a voice. It is loud. Very loud. She is learning not to use it as much and responds when her foster mom talks to her. But her new owner understands this girl has a lot to say and sometimes it sounds like a screech. Lavendar is better with women, but warms up to men. Men have to put in more work to earn her trust.

Lavendar does not handle change well. She was adopted once but returned after less than 48 hours when she simply couldn't make the transition. We all learned a lot from this experience. Lavendar MUST have a home with an experienced chihuahua owner that understands the breed. She WILL be a nervous wreck and act crazily for the first 72 hours; then she will settle down. This girl is wonderful - she just has to get comfortable.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Shy but curious.

Other tips and tidbits: Lavender's estimated birthday is 9/23/2018

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Noah! I'm a 3 year old boy and I currently weigh 34 lbs. I was found as a stray and brought to the shelter. No one came to claim me, so, here I am. I am only 34 lbs right now, but I am very skinny. The shelter has been taking good care of me to get me back into the best shape. In addition to me being found very skinny, I was also found to have Heartworms. Thankfully for me, The Humane Society of Marion County will treat me for this (Please ask Kennel Staff or the Front Desk about Heartworm Fostering). Since I was a stray, not a lot is known about me or my past. I can be a little nervous and stiff around other dogs, perhaps I'll come around in time. I am not a fan of cats and I have not been tested for my temperament around children yet. I do like treats and will gladly 'sit' for you. If you think I'm cute and you want to give me the best life, please ask a Kennel Staff Member to arrange a meet and greet for us. Thanks!

Love, 
Noah

animal.description:
Kimiko (Kimmie) is a blue and white female Pit Bull, born September 2019. She was found as a stray in Missouri. Kimmie is a playful girl, who can be mouthy while playing therefore she needs a home with no kids under the age of 12. Kimmie is house trained, kennel trained, great with all pets. She can jump a 4ft fence with no problem, so a 6ft privacy fence would be best. Kimmie is currently undergoing heartworm treatment while in foster, and is excited to find her perfect home to start her future fresh start in.

Before applying to adopt Kimiko, you need to be familiar with your local breed-specific legislation regarding Pit Bulls. Applicants must live within 50 miles of the Omaha/Council Bluffs area.

The suggested adoption donation for Kimiko is $400. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Are you in search of a friendly, energetic companion to go on adventures with you? Look no further! Meet Lucy, a 1 year old Border Collie mix weighing in at 40lbs.

Lucy is currently in a foster home in the Olympia, Washington area. To apply, please fill out an application at www.doggedly.org/adoption-app

Lucy is a beautiful, young Border Collie mix with a beautiful, silky black coat and piercing golden eyes. This stunning girl is very young, estimated to be around 1 year old and has a lot of love to give! Sadly, Lucy was found as a stray and ended up in a high kill shelter pregnant. The stress of the shelter caused Lucy to go into labor and she gave birth to 5 beautiful puppies in the shelter clinic. Due to Lucy's young age, we believe that she became pregnant during her very 
 first heat cycle, ultimately setting up her newborn puppies for a rough life.

Luckily for Lucy, she was pulled by Doggedly within a day of giving birth and placed with an experienced foster home to nurse her newborn babies. This didn't go as planned, and sadly Lucy was infested with parasites, which she passed on to her babies through her breast milk. Within days, her puppies started to cry in pain with bloody diarrhea. Lucy was absolutely distraught and being a new mom, had no idea what to do. She picked up her puppies and carried them around one at a time in a panic, before ultimately rejecting her litter and denying them milk. Two of Lucy's puppies died within the first 10 days of birth. The last 3 were taken in for emergency care with blood transfusions and hospitalization. Unfortunately, the runt baby passed and only two male puppies remained. Lucy's 2 surviving puppies are about 4 weeks old and were bottle fed with a foster. They are thriving and doing amazing.

Once Lucy's milk dried up, we spayed her, since she was already separated from her pups. Since then, this magnificent young pup has been enjoying the spoiled life in her foster home.

Lucy is as easy as it comes with high energy herding breeds. She is energetic, excited and loves to chase balls, play with toys and loves the company of other dogs. Lucy is wonderful on a leash, loves car rides and outdoors adventures. She would be an amazing running partner and has the drive and stamina as a herding breed to keep up with your daily activity. True to her breed, Lucy will require more exercise and mental stimulation than other breeds, as a highly intelligent and energetic girl. Her ideal home would have 1 or more energetic dogs, or the opportunity to socialize often. Due to her rambunctious nature, we recommend that Lucy only be placed with older children. Lucy has not been tested with cats.

Lucy is extremely intelligent and highly food motivated. Her highest motivator is praise, and she wants so badly to please her humans. This silly girl will roll over at the slightest hint of a belly rub, which is her favorite thing on the planet! At times, Lucy still behaves like a high energy puppy. She would do best in a home with the time and resources to dedicate to basic training and beyond, since she is a working breed.
animal.name: Lucy the Border Collie

animal.description: Andy is a Doberman/ Black Lab mix rescued from a high kill shelter just in the nick of time. He is house trained, smart and knows many commands. Andy comes to his name, and knows many commands including sit, stay and down! Andy was seen by our private vet and is a very healthy boy about 7 yrs old. He had torn a ligament on his knee, and we got him the surgery that he needs. His recovery is going well and he is back to normal. He currently weighs about 60 lbs. He has a lean body with slim legs. Andy likes to play with his toys, but isn't rambunctious. Andy is house trained, knows many commands. Andy is a loving dog who deserves a home. Unfortunately, we have to board Andy because we do not have any available foster homes. Andy deserves better than that, and we are eager to find him a foster or forever home. He should go to an adult home as an only dog. He wants to be an alpha dog, so should go to a home with doggie experience. Andy has worked with a trainer, and is ready to go the right home. He is very loving and playful, and can be quite the sweetheart. He just needs an experienced adopter who can give him the structure and exercise. Andy is fully vaccinated, neutered, and microchipped. If you live in the Los Angeles area and would like to meet Andy, please complete our adoption application found on dexterfoundation.com If you can't adopt, can you at least foster, or know someone who can? We need a foster or adopter in the Los Angeles area. Thanks for sharing.

animal.description:
Meet Starlight, an adorable 8 month old fluff who had a very rough start to life. Starlight is a poodle chihuahua mix weighing in at just under 10lbs. She was found a stray with brother Midnight as a sickly puppy living in a pile of trash.

Starlight is currently in the greater Seattle area. We would love for both pups to be adopted together, or go into a home with one or more playful pups the same size. To apply to adopt Starlight apply at  www.doggedly.org/adoption-app

Starlight and her brother Midnight were found at just 3 weeks old, living in a pile of garbage in the streets of Mexico. A Good Samaritan found the pair and brought them back to Texas, but both puppies soon became extremely ill. Midnight was the worst of the pair, screaming in pain with a tight, sore stomach. As it turns out, Midnight was infested with intestinal parasites and was given to a rescue, where he was rushed to the vet for medical care. Midnight suffered from seizures, diarrhea, anemia and hypoglycemia from an extreme parasite overload for such a small, frail puppy. He was dewormed, given antibiotics and seizure medications to stabilize him and was tube fed until he gained strength. Midnight was hospitalized for a month to be tube fed and have his blood sugar levels monitored, as would suddenly go limp from low blood sugar. His sister Starlight received fluid therapy, antibiotics and deworming and was able to leave to a foster home after a week. 

When both pups were finally healthy enough to be reunited with a foster home, they needed round the clock care from a medical foster. Both puppies were hypoglycemic and would become cold and limp if not feed consistently. They still had large, wormy bellies and needed to be dewormed weekly, as they consistently had diarrhea and digestive issues for the first few months, which put them at risk for anemia and dehydration. These little pups were fighters and beat the odds of survival, weighing in at only 1lb at 4 weeks old when they first came into the rescue. Starlight and Midnight are now 6 months old, active and extremely healthy little love bugs. They are both ready to finally leave the nest and find their forever homes.

Starlight and Midnight are both extremely social dogs, that enjoy the company of larger dogs, cats and children. Due to their small size, we do require a home with kids over than 6 years old. Larger dogs will be considered on a case by case basis, based on temperament around small dogs. Starlight is an extremely confident puppy that loves to play. Midnight is the baby of the pair, since he spent the beginning of his life being handled and tube fed, he knows that he is a little prince and loves to be spoiled. Both dogs are extremely friendly, curious and adore their humans. They love to play and tap dance for meal time. As much as they love each other, both pups are now old enough to go to separate homes. They would also thrive together, as they have been separated long enough to develop separately from one another with no concerns for littermate syndrome. Starlight and Midnight are both very independent, rambunctious little pups that are ready to take on and explore the world!

Both puppies are currently learning to potty train and are trained to pee on potty pads. They are kennel trained and have started to leash train. They love short walks in the grass, and absolutely adore little adventures where they can explore outdoors.

Starlight is spayed, microchipped, and has received 3 rounds of puppy boosters, Bordetella vaccine, Canine Influenza vaccines, plus rabies vaccine. Puppy kindergarten classes are included in his adoption fee. Starlight has no known food allergies, but she can be a picky eater. She does require a high quality diet formulated for toy breeds (she is currently eating Fromm Gold Puppy Small Breed with wet food and fish oil), to fuel her growing puppy body. Her beautiful wiry coat is low maintenance, but does require regular bathing and brushing retain it's soft and shiny glow. A home familiar with extra small breed dogs is preferred.
animal.name: Starlight - Pickle Twins

Woodstock is a very sweet, affectionate, long-legged boy who loves long walks and chasing after balls. He knows his basic commands and the volunteers are polishing up his leash training. Check out the video of Woodstock on our weekly Shelter Dog Hike! Come meet him at our Costa Mesa location.

---
We know there are some 3rd party websites giving mis-information on the location of the pet you may be interested in. For correct information, please visit the location of the animal's name listed directly after their name, and visit the bio for more information. Thank you!! (Ex: "Sparky - Chino Hills Location will mean you go to Chino Hills; "Fluffy - Claremont Location will mean you go to Claremont; and "Fido - Costa Mesa Location will mean you go to Costa Mesa) There may also be mis-information about the status of an available pet. If the animal is no longer listed on our main website, it is no longer available for adoption. For accurate information please visit pricelesspetrescue.org

animal.description:
Dancer has had a rough young life, and a rough road to recovery…Dancer is a beautiful 1 yr old blond golden who was surrendered to GRRAND by owners in southern Indiana who were unable to manage the expense of her medical needs. They had only acquired Dancer 5 months earlier from another owner and while with them she became very sick. They spent $1,500 on her with 2 different vet clinics who were unable to diagnose her illness. Dancer has severely swollen joints and nose, bleeding sores and ruptures to her skin, had to have an eye removed because it also became infected, and lameness. When GRRAND acquired this sweet girl, we took her immediately to the emergency vet where she was quickly diagnosed with Blastomycosis, a severe fungal disease that is systemic and oftentimes fatal. The fungus is acquired from wet or moist soil, often around ponds. Dancer’s former owners said that she loved to dig in the pond on their property! Dancer is now on expensive medications to treat the fungus and we hope that her therapy has come soon enough to save her life, and her other eye. This girl is in a lot of pain, but continues to be nothing but total sweetness. She is in a wonderful foster home with a foster mom who is monitoring her progress around the clock. We are so grateful that at this time, Dancer continues to eat and drink and doesn’t seem to require hospitalization. We are looking for donations to cover the cost of Dancer’s treatment which will extend for many months, perhaps as long as a year or so.

At this time, we are unable to process any applications that are outside of the geographic areas listed below:
Greater Louisville, KY (including adjacent southern Indiana)
Greater Lexington, KY
Southern Indiana Counties:  Clark and Floyd
Ohio Counties: Hamilton, Butler, Warren, some areas within Clermont county, Montgomery and Green
Northern KY Counties: Boone, Kenton and Campbell
 
To inquire about a specific dog, we require that you first submit an adoption application.  Visit http://grrand.org/online-adoption-application/  to access our online application.  You do not need to fill out an application for each dog you are interested in learning more about.  Once your application is reviewed a GRRAND volunteer will contact you to begin the process.  Our Adoption Placement Coordinator will work with you to find a dog with the characteristics to best fit your family.

2 yr SF 55 lbs mixed breed

She has a booming voice that takes you by surprise, but if your redirect her she is just the daintiest soul. She learned to kennel quickly for cheese and as she becomes more brave everyday the world is turning into a land of opportunity and fun instead of caution and concern.

She is a masterpiece of a soul coming alive with each day.
Is she a straightforward girl?? If you are clear with what you expect from her she will do anything and everything to please you. Is she all the way there yet? No. . but so quickly she is picking up on how she is to get there.

If you are interested in meeting this rare gem of a girl please fill out an application at sfcva.org
She is waiting for you!!!

animal.description:
Meet Maggie!

Sugar Magnolia (Maggie) - This Olde English Bulldog beauty queen is 5 years old, and sweet as can be. She will become your shadow in the house, with a cute nub tail wiggling furiously behind her whenever she looks at you. At other times, she will simply lean into you, and it’s impossible to resist bending down to give her love. Her size is substantial, but she is very much a lap dog. 

Maggie is very well-behaved, and will fit into most homes from Day 1. If you work from home, she will usually lay in a dog bed next to you, either quietly chewing a bone or loudly taking a nap. She doesn’t mind spending time in her kennel, and has always lived in a home so she is very well-mannered. Maggie was surrendered because she cannot be in a home with other animals, especially dogs. Her reaction is significant enough that her new home will need to proactively ensure that there are never dogs in her proximity (including on walks, at the vet, etc…), but these accommodations are not necessarily that onerous, especially for homebodies. However, she will need to be in a home with no children who are more prone to accidentally leaving a door open. If you’d like to meet Maggie, please fill out an application at NewOrleansBulldogs.com/adopt.

All of our dogs come fully-vaccinated, temperament-tested, and resources to set you and your dog up for success when adopting. Thank you for your support of our rescue!

animal.description:
Baby
Rottweiler Mix
Female
8 years old
82 lbs.

Hey there, I’m Baby, a sweet, loving dog who is happiest being where my person is. I’ve learned a lot about trusting people again in my foster home and I can’t wait to find a quiet, experienced human (or two!) who can give me all the love and adoration I so much deserve. 

I have a pretty medium amount of energy and will be active when you feel like being active, but will laze about if you’re relaxing. I also have a nice voice and like to sing along with passing ambulances. I love to play tug and chew on my toys, but cuddling with my people is the best. I do fine when my foster parents are away from the house but I just love when they’re home to give me all the love. 

I do bond really well with my humans and am affectionate and happy overall. However, new people still make me nervous and I need a slow introduction to new people overall. I’ve learned SO much in my foster home and my foster parents really helped me build confidence with treats, redirection, and other positive reinforcement training. However, I can be reactive to strangers walking by me (men more so than women) so I need thoughtful management on walks and a slow introduction to visitors in the house (once I trust you in the house, I’m great!) I also need to be in a home where there are adults only since my need to warm up isn’t the right match for kids. I’m also really uncomfortable at vet visits so I need an understanding vet and a thoughtful plan for any vet visits. 

I also am not a fan of other dogs and react to them when I’m on leash and in the house. Therefore, I need to be the only animal in the home and I can’t be in an apartment as I need that private yard space where I can relax and not interact with other dogs. 

If you’re looking for a pup who can just be your best friend, who will always be by your side, and you have experience with positive reinforcement and a general patience for pups who need some extra patience and love, I’d be such a lovely match for you! Please email my friends at adopt@pawscoadoptions.org and check out this information page: https://pawsco.org/adopt/adoption-process.

Gender: Female 
Age:12 months 
Breed: Terrier Mix

My name is Stevie Nicks and the last human I was with pushed me out of their car along the side of the road with my siblings. I thought they were coming with us because our collars and leashes were still attached, but they just drove off!  Despite this heartbreaking betrayal, I LOVE people!  I’m a velcro dog that loves cuddling with humans and I expect belly rubs.  While I do well with other pups, I am more interested in you so I might not be a playmate for another pup in your home but will co-exist just fine. While I enjoy my naps while you are home working or chilling out watching football on the couch, I do have quite a bit of energy so I need someone who will make sure I get exercise. I’m making progress on my potty training but it’s still in progress.  So far I’m not much of a barker or chewer, but I’m still getting settled in at my foster home.  I have not yet been introduced to a crate, so if you plan to crate me, a slow and gradual introduction would be needed. My foster mom says I’m one of the most adoptable dogs she’s had the pleasure of fostering, so you better hurry up and apply for me!  The rescue gets 100s of emails a day so the best first step is to fill out the adoption application which is required prior to a phone call and meet and greet:

animal.description:
Lucy is 9-year-old dog (doesn’t act like it at all!) surrendered from a good family whose situation changed.  She has settled in very nicely with her foster family & always wants to be where the family is, but she is happy to watch events from the comfort of her dog bed.  At several points during the day she gets up and does a check to make sure she knows where every member of the family is and, once everyone is accounted for, she settles down in the room with the most occupants.  

Lucy loves snuggles: if you sit down on the floor you’ll find yourself with a dog in your lap in no time, and on the rare occasion you invite her onto the couch or bed with you, she’ll be up in a heartbeat and will certainly not be the first to leave.  She will never turn down a scratch behind her ears, but she is also not demanding of attention. 
 
Lucy is a calm and steady household presence.  She lives with 2 young boys and the commotion of the busy house is of no bother to her.   
 
She has good household manners: she knows sit and down, she waits well at the door, she is a hopeful presence at the dinner table but does not beg.  She does not jump on people or lick.  She rarely barks in the home.  We do find her on the couch occasionally.  

Lucy does not love the crate but after a minute or two of whining she settles right down and then is fine in the crate through the night or for a couple of hours during the day. 
 
Despite Lucy’s steadiness, she is an enthusiastic greeter when anyone returns home after being out, she has a boundless puppy enthusiasm for food, and she still loves to get outside and run and chase squirrels and birds, and she can’t resist a squeaky toy.  On leash, she likes to be nose-down and on-the-scent so walks are purposeful rather than casual.  In the yard she barks at every passerby whether person, dog, or car (though she does not bark when on leash).
 
Lucy would be best in a household that wants a quiet dog to be a faithful by-your-side companion.  She would be fine in a household with children of any age.  She much prefers running free in the yard to walks, so a home with a fenced yard is preferable.  

Lucy did live with another dog, but that dog was placed before we evaluated her. We noticed in her initial foster home that she does not seem to be very comfortable around other dogs.  She is probably best in a single-dog household. She did display some resource guarding issues with her food both towards children and other dogs when there were other dogs in the home:in her presence. Her original owner confirmed the same.  However, current foster hasn't seen any display of this at all (there are no other dogs in the home). So we do think she would be best as a single dog but would be open to a meet and greet with another dog if the family was committed to feeding her separate and understood they’re may not be able to be toys/high value items in her possession when other dogs are present.  

If you are interested  in meeting Lucy please submit an adoption application at: www.GSPrescuenj.com.

Renzo is a 4-5 year old, male, Siberian Husky who is extremely smart and eager to please. He knows sit, down, stay, leave it and drop it. Renzo loves to play (especially fetch) and is the energizer bunny while outdoors but as soon as he is indoors, he is mellow as can be.

Renzo is super friendly with people. He loves giving kisses and being pet but can be very stubborn, as most huskies are, so he needs to be in a husky savvy home with a confident owner that can give him gentle correcting. He also has typical husky talk, and will tell you like it is. He and the female Siberian Husky, he currently lives with in his foster home, have contests to see who can talk the loudest.

Renzo would do best with a calmer, female dog, or being the only dog in the home. He does have a bit of resource guarding when it comes to food and treats but easily manageable by giving him commands and feeding him separately away from other dogs.

Renzo is the best pup, does not dig outdoors and does not chew up anything inside or out. How can you pass up a husky that doesn't dig or chew?! Renzo is looking for someone to give him the best life that he deserves and to have an owner that will always be by his side, something that he hasn't had much of in the past.

When you hear the phrase, "Man's best friend", Renzo fits that to a T.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Snow, as in Snow White.  I am about 13 lbs, 4 years old, sweet, and playful.  I am looking for a home along with my brother Charming (Prince Charming).

I was one of 9 puppies born after our mommy was pulled from a very high kill shelter in Houston, TX (on the day she was to be put to sleep, as she was very pregnant with us, and they had no place for her).  I was born 10/7/2016.  My siblings and I have been trying to find homes in Houston since we were little, but it is very hard to find people there that want to take care of us the right way.  We sat at hundreds of events, and people would say how cute we were, but we never found our places.  We have 4 siblings that found their forever families in the PNW, now it is our turn. 

I am super sweet.  I can be a little bit shy at first, and will need a few days to acclimate to new situations, but once I trust my people, things are great.  My brother is the same way, so we are not the best candidates for doggie day cares and dog parks.  We play very well together, and will play with toys with our people,and that is plenty of entertainment.  We are still on the smaller side, so we will need people to accompany us outside to potty/ etc.  We do know how to use potty pads too (as long as they are not on carpet… sometimes they confuse where the edge is if on carpet).  Potty pads can be a great option if there is yucky weather/etc.  I am not used to children, so small children will not be a good thing for us.  I loooovvve kitties.  Sometimes I love them a bit too much… I lick all over their faces sometimes to show them how much I love them, and for some reason, some of them don’t like this.  I would never hurt them, and have been around them my whole life… I wish they understood that.  Some do.  Some let me kiss them and play with me and let me snuggle with them.  One kitten I recently met, chased me too…. It was SO FUN!!!!  If I didn’t love my brother as much as I do, the rescue was going to say we should go to a new home together we did so well lol.  They couldn’t find the kitty, and panicked running outside at 3 am etc, thinking maybe somehow he got out, but found him cuddling in my bed with me.  It was kind of funny to us.   Well, that is all for now… time to go play.  Let my rescue people know if you’d like to meet me, and after you fill out an application to be an approved adopter, they will schedule a time for us to meet each other.  They will bring me to your house, as that is the best environment to meet in.  Oh, I am fully vetted and up to date on my healthcare too.  Please try to be within an hour (or close to that) of the Seattle area.

Adoption fee:  $600 each (this includes a few months of heartworm/ flea medication, a leash/ harness for her, having recently refreshed vaccines (including a 3 year rabies vaccine), and a few other supplies)

animal.description:
Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.

Elle is one of eleven puppies abandoned at two weeks of age.  The puppies have been bottle raised and in foster homes, and are now ready for adoption.  They have had their first two sets of three puppy vaccinations.  At this time, they can only be adopted in the general Springfield, Nixa, Ozark area.   In order to adopt now, the adopter must be able to get Elle to her last vet appointment at Best Friends Animal Hospital in Ozark on January 19, for her last DA2PPV, rabies vaccination, and her spay.  She will need to be at Best Friends between 7:30 and 8:00, and picked up after three that day. 

Elle has been exposed to house cats, and although curious, she does not chase them. She is a snuggler, and a very intelligent puppy.  She loves her sister, Vee, and would love to be adopted with her.  The girls are already fairly good about using pee pads and a potty patch with ASTRO turf

Elle will make a wonderful addition to any family with children over ten years of age.
 
Please complete and return the adoption application to meet Elle, or any of our adoptable dogs.
http://www.route66rescueinc.com/adoption-application.html Thank you for visiting our site. Please come back often.

Miss Penny is an absolute delight! She was returned to her original rescue after her owner passed away. She would love to find a cozy home where she can bond with her forever human. animal.description:
Moony is a ridiculous, lovey boy. He had a rough start and never learned social skills. He is submissive to humans and eager to please.

He LOVES tennis balls and tough squeaky toys. His favorite toy is his squeaky Kong bunny. He needs lots of play, exercise and affection. Needs room in the yard to run. He gives the best kisses. (His teeth get brushed daily!) Moon is a ridiculous goofball who doesn't know his own size. He likes to sit in your lap and he enjoys feeling small and protected. 

He likes sticking his head out the window on car rides and getting whipped cream treats from Starbucks. Known commands: sit, heel, catch, down, lay down, wait, up, come, and free. He comes if you whistle. He understands "stay and "place but doesn't always do it. He loves playing fetch with tennis balls and rope toys. He gives endless kisses! He hides under the bed when it rains or if he's scared. He is crate trained but gets depressed if he has to stay in the crate a lot. He needs a lot of human presence and love. In return, he will love you with all of his big, goofy heart. He will let you flop him onto his back and play with his paws, and he gets this relaxed, goofy grin. He seems to always do better if he has a strong male presence around; a male "pack leader seems to make him feel more secure. He's very sensitive to his owner's moods and becomes fearful/hides if his owner is upset or crying. 

Moon does not do well with other animals and needs to be the only pet in the household. Moon is available for adoption in Texas ONLY.

As a small organization, we cannot answer emails about each of our pets. Please fill out an application for more information on this dog, and one of our adoption coordinators will contact you.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.LUCIA IS CURRENTLY BEING FOSTERED IN ILLINOIS

Lucia is a 3 1/2 year old, Blue, 130 pound female Neapolitan Mastiff. She is being fostered in Missouri. An individual rescued her and her sister Lilla from a dog auction, and then immediately surrendered them to Mastino Rescue. Very little is known about their previous life.. We speculate that they were used to living in a wide open space in their previous lives before rescue because many things in life are very new and frightening to them. She is a little cautious/shy/scared of new things but will build more confidence every day with love and security. She takes just a moment to warm up to new people. Once she does, she wants nothing but for you to be her person. Lucia will have to learn how to walk on a leash, be potty trained and learn how to be a dog. We do not know how she will do with other dogs/cats at this time. She will be spayed, UTD on shots, HW tested and parasite-free. If you are interested in adopting Lucia, please go to our website at www.mastinorescue.org and complete a Family Profile. Please remember you must own your home, no children under the age of 10 and have a 6 foot privacy fence due to our insurance requirements. STAY TUNED FOR MORE UPDATES TO FOLLOW.

Sweet Buddy just celebrated his one year birthday a few days ago and is loving life!   This handsome fellow is full of energy and loves to run, romp and play to expend his energy.    Very smart, eager to learn, and energetic best describe this Walker Hound / Beagle mix who loves every human he meets . . . he has never met a stranger.    Buddy is very good about staying in his playlot, gets along with his playmates and other dogs and he is crate and house trained. 

Learning to walk on the leash is coming along quickly and he eagerly sits when asked …….especially if a delicious treat is offered. Buddy does like to find interesting distractions to bark at when he isn’t otherwise occupied but, keep this fellow active, and you have found a wonderful pet.

The successful owner will have a way to keep Buddy safely contained, likely have an active pet to help him expend his energy through running and playing OR be an exceptionally active person who can challenge this good looking tri-color both physically and intellectually.

If you are interested in adopting this energetic fellow, please fill out an application via our website at godbeycreekcaninerescue.org/    Buddy is located at Godbey Creek Canine Rescue, in Mocksville, NC and you can phone 336.972.4511 for more information.

animal.description:
Prince is a magnificent 1-1/2 year old male Chocolate Labrador Retriever mix who was surrendered by his owner on December 2, 2020 along with his two brothers (Damon and Rebel) because he was no longer able to give them the time and attention that they deserved.

Prince has a chocolate brown short smooth coat, a large white bib on his chest which is sprinkled with brown freckles, a long tail, and an adorable face with a milk chocolate nose, a chubby muzzle, and short floppy ears. 

Prince has a sweet, very demure disposition and a friendly personality.  Prince was clearly 'out of his comfort zone' when HSOV Kennel Tech Madison Barnett took him outdoors for his photo session.  Prince reluctantly walked on a leash and accompanied Madison to a grassy area where he posed for one quick picture and then decided he wanted to go back indoors.  So most of Prince's photos were taken as he begged to get back into the shelter.   This was a 'first' for us since most often the dogs are reluctant to go back inside to the kennels after their photo sessions.  

We look forward to taking more flattering pictures of this beautiful boy but wanted to share the ones we were able to capture so that potential adopters would know that Prince is in our shelter and is looking for a fabulous home.

Prince weighs 53 lbs. He doesn't appear to have had much walking-on-a-leash experience, but he is a clever young man who will quickly master that new skill with help from our kennel techs.

Prince will be neutered before being adopted by his new family.

UPDATE: Prince was neutered on January 18, 2021 and was also given rabies vaccine.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm FINN.  I'm a 3-4 yr old neutered male.  I'm fun and sweet at the same time.  I do miss the feeling of having someone that can make me smile and feel appreciated. I'm definitely a house dog and I'm very affectionate. I'm not a fan of livestock or delivery trucks and I think I'm allergic to cats!  I'm a very strong dog and a good protector but I like it when there is someone to hold and snuggle me the first and last thing everyday!  Someone that will look past my faults and love me for who I am. Someone that I can call mine. If you like tall, dark and handsome, I could be your man.

Note:  Great Pyrenees are considered a Giant Breed.  Average weight can be 100lbs. or more.  They bark, shed and have a wanderlust, so secure fences are a must have.  They are NOT off leash dogs and a Pyr off leash is called a "dis'a'Pyr".  Some Pyrs do well with other dogs and some don't because by the virtue of their breed traits they were bred to keep out intruders and can consider some dogs as intruders. While they make wonderful pets and family dogs, they aren't for everyone so be sure to understand and learn about the breed traits of this breed or any breed you might be considering.

animal.description:
Hi there, pitty lovers!  My name is Meatloaf and I would so love to start the new year  in my forever home!  You see, I was found wandering on my own and taken in to stay at this nice shelter.  That was my lucky day because they are very good to me here.  I love my caretakers (I know they love me, too), but I’ve been waiting SO LONG for a real home of my own where I can hang my leash forever. 

What would you like to know about me?  As you can see in my pictures, I’m a pitty….they tell me I’m very handsome.   I am a big boy, weighing in at 75 – 80 pounds.  I’m  8 years old and my human friends at the shelter say that I am super sweet.  They know I can't stay here forever and really want to help me find my forever home.  I have learned lots of good manners since I came here.  I  sit nicely for treats and wait while I’m getting harnessed for my walks.  I'm still a work in progress, but I try really hard to please.  

I’m house trained and (of course), kennel trained.  I also walk well on a leash, but sometimes new situations can get me worked up which makes me jump and bite at my leash.  I’m working hard to overcome that – and I know I'll keep improving with a confident leader.  When it comes to other dogs, I like them just fine.  I have to admit that my greeting skills need a little polish because I get a bit excited  to say hello when new ones come to the shelter.

Here are some things that I’m hoping for in my new family:  Most important is a patient, calm home where my people will be willing to give me time to figure out what’s expected of me.  They should be experienced with my breed – or large dogs.  I would never intentionally harm anyone but, since I’m a strong energetic boy, my home should be with adults or teens.  I wouldn't want to accidently knock over a young child if I get a little jumpy.  A fenced yard where I can run around and play would be nice, but not required because I mostly just want to be wherever my people are.

I am neutered and up to date with vaccines.  I’m also heart worm negative and on monthly preventative.  If you are a pitty lover, I hope you will open your heart and home to help me become the best dog I can be.  I promise to be your devoted companion.  I’m not perfect, but if you think I may be perfect for you, please email Chris at rescue3@earthlink.net and she’ll contact you. She can arrange a meet and greet in CT.  Can’t wait to meet you!! 

THIS IS A COURTESY LISTING

But don’t let his size fool you, he is really very sweet.  He’s big mush who loves his people. He is dog selective, so we suggest he be the dog only in the home.  Cats are unknown.  Due to his size, we recommend no young children.  He prefers a yard so he can run and play.  He loves his down time too and will make a great tv buddy or book reading pal.  He loves walks but is fine just playing in his own yard as well.  Spencer is neutered; fully vetted.
 
If you are interested in being Spencer’s forever home and best buddy, please contact adoptions@paws-li.org or go to our FB page or call the number listed below.
 
Pioneers for Animals Welfare Society, Inc.

animal.description:
Please fill out the application now if you are interested as we are still closed to the public and doing meet & greets and adoptions by appointment only.

Frida Pawhlo is an Australian Cattle Dog/Blue Heeler mix girl that was born in December 2019 and weighs 32 pounds. She is also deaf.

Frida recently went out on an outting with one of our wonderful volunteers and he is what she had to say, "Frida was VERY happy to get out for an adventure with me today and I must say she is AMAZING company! I had to remind myself she cannot hear.  She gets around so well but jumps if she is touched from behind.  Fast movement also makes her a bit nervous but she recovers very quickly with gentle affection and calm reassurance.  She knows sit (sign language) and I'm pretty sure she can read lips.  She is VERY into eye contact!
 
We grabbed some vittles at Wimpies in Soddy Daisy then went across the street to eat at a table near Poe's Tavern.  I planned to share my ice water with Frida and put half in a bowl for her but she submerged her entire snout into my cup before I could protest. 
 
While I ate my lunch, Frida practiced her SIT and was rewarded with some bites of Wimpies cornbread.  I tried to get some pretty posed pics in front of the Tavern but Frida COULD NOT stop rolling and wiggling around in the grass.  Frida is a fun loving girl.
 
We took a short walk in the park.  Frida saw others but never barked.  In fact, she didn't bark one time while we were out and about (but I am told she does bark some in her kennel). Frida loved chillin' on the dock in the sun and watching the birds.
 
Frida is such a good girl.  Due to the fact she is deaf, she probably should not be in a home with small children.  She is SO affectionate and calm.  She will thrive in a home where she gets lots of attention and love.  It would be really good for Frida if she has an adopter who is committed to teaching her how to communicate through sign language.  Frida wants to be a good girl and is very anxious to learn."
 


We're open Wednesday - Sunday 12 - 5 p.m but are doing meet & greets and adoptions by appointment only.  

The adoption fee is $90 which includes a free veterinary exam within 2 weeks of adoption at local participating vets, up to date vaccinations, heartworm test,  heartworm preventative, dewormer, flea preventative, microchip, & spay or neuter.

If you are interested in this pet, please fill out our ADOPTION APPLICATION at https://goo.gl/forms/9FdDBiPU5aa5ySTv1

Visit our website at www.PetPlacementCenter.com

animal.description:
Cowboy was recently rescued as a found dog.  He had been surviving in sub-freezing temperatures with no shelter or food.  At the time he was rescued, this beautiful heeler was very scared and skittish (but it was obvious he wanted help).  This is normal behavior for a dog in deep survival mode.

Cowboy is a great dog in the process of learning to trust.  He is friendly, but unsure of what to expect in a shelter environment.  We think he will open up more quickly just as soon as he can get homed with someone who understands the needs of the breed (and specifically the needs of this guy who has obviously survived some very difficult circumstances).

Someone is going to get a fabulous dog when they adopt this guy.  He has such great potential.  You can see it in his eyes.  

If you are the right one to build up Cowboy's confidence, and if you can help him learn to trust in the goodness of human beings, please email us for a pre-adoption questionnaire.  woof@slvaws.org

Once you are approved for adoption, you may set up an appointment to come meet Cowboy at our shelter near San Luis, CO.  We practice safe COVID-19 protocols.

animal.description: Poor Jonah has found himself surrendered at 12 years old after being adopted in August of 2018 from a shelter in Chicago. Knowing this, he needs a special home that understands not to startle a deaf pup! He is not aggressive here with anyone, but we know to get the attention of dogs that can't hear us coming. He is housetrained and loves walks and running around. He may be 12 years old...but no one told him! P.S. I have a 20 year old JRT personally so they can live very long lives when well loved!

animal.description:
Jordyn is a lovely dog, approximately 6 years of age, who has been here since she was a puppy.  She has not been offered for adoption prior to this time, but we feel she would enjoy being an only dog in a home that can meet her needs and decided we would see if that special someone is out there.  Jordyn is well trained,  well behaved, and extremely affectionate but quite timid and reserved and it will take her time to warm up to a new person.  The following are the requirements for her new home:

Adult female home - Jordyn is frightened of children and men
Fenced yard.
A human who will be available to her often during the day - someone who works from home would be ideal
No other animals.  Jordyn does not do well with other dogs and might well chase cats.
Rural home - loud noises and heavy traffic are very difficult for her.
Not a livestock guardian dog - indoor pet home only

An understanding of the temperament of the guardian breeds will be a big plus!

Jordyn is healthy, spayed, current on vaccines and heartworm preventative.  Her adoption fee is $250.  For an online adoption application, please email reverence@ottcmail.com.  A telephone conversation will take place AFTER an approved application is received.  A meet/greet, veterinary references, and a home visit are also requirements for our adoptions.  Potential applicants should reside within a 50 mile radius of Ithaca, New York or in the Rochester area.

animal.description:
Chandler and Joey were rescued from a shelter. Both were sad and timid at the shelter. They have been neglected unhealthy and have severe flea dermatitis. Once out of the shelter he was very happy friendly and sweet. Good with other dogs. He needs healthy food basic home training and TLC. Chandler and Joey are already separated into two different foster homes.
Update from Foster Home: Chandler truly is a lovely and sweet boy. He's not a big fan of loud noises or fast motions so I have been slowly introducing him to new experiences at his level. We have given him an area in the house where he can just relax process his new reality and feel safe. He is a little shy when meeting new people but will definitely warm up over time. Fortunately he has a very big appetite and is very treat motivated! I'm happy to report that he does not show any signs of food aggression. He also loves other dogs and loves to be in their company! He just wants to receive and give love so much but is wary possibly due to little human interaction in his past. Needs dog experienced adults. Chandler will surely share his affectionate personality with an appropriate family that understands his yearning to be loved. House-training is in progress. Need home with attached yard.
On 8/31/20 3rd vet exam and neuter the vet told us that he has 4 front lower teeth worn down (common with neglect case and from being locked in a kennel & chewing cage). 3 Vets confirmed they did not need extraction. Prior vets and shelter vet did not inform us of need to remove any teeth. Only noted tartar at shelter. His skin is now healed from the flea dermatitis. Looking great. Loves food and eating well.
Vet confirmed at time of neuter exam no dental extraction needed for worn lower bottom teeth.
Chandler is very bonded to his foster home with women and men. Also great with neighbors older kids and other dogs that may visit out front. However he will need time to adjust emotionally to new potential adopters since he wants to follow his foster home. He would love a dog friend at home that is polite and not try to challenge him.
Update: Chandler was adopted but returned within the month due to sudden fear issues and nipped their adult daughter. We are unsure why he has these random fear issues when he seemed so happy go lucky before. He needs a very quiet routine and experienced adult home with yard to work thru his fear issues.
Update 1/11/21: Chandler is crate trained. He generally gets along fine with cats and has learned to ignore his feline companions. I have taught him how to sit down shake hand spin roll over and working on soldiering (low body crawl)!!! He's intelligent and bonds through training!! Chandler is taking fluoxetine daily and trazodone on an as-needed basis. So far the medication seems to be helping calm his nervousness. He no longer looks around endlessly or in fear of noises in his surroundings.

animal.description:
Noelle (watch my video at the shelter and me at my foster home!) was neglected and thin when she was abandoned at a dog park. Shelter took her in and started her vet care. She had fly bites on her ear was thin had flea dermatitis needed dental (worn bottom teeth) and overall unhealthy.
After a month at the shelter her time was up. She had no options left and was getting kennel stressed. Thanks to our foster home we were able to rescue her. Noelle is people friendly and loves attention. With dogs at the shelter play-yard she needed to meet first and then fine hanging out.
She does listen to corrections. When finally out of the shelter she did do excitement barking at dogs at a distance. We have to see if she was barking because she was excited to be out finally (after a month) or reactive to dog park. GSD do like to talk. Noelle did fine on walk and already knows 'sit' and 'down' for treats. She loves to play ball and will bring it back & drop it.
Noelle is now relaxing at her foster home after her spay and dental/extractions. She needs time to relax learn and get healthier. Noelle is beautiful and smart. She will need an experienced GSD guardian. Adult-only and home with yard. More info. to come from her Foster Home.YouTube: https://youtu.be/zKA79Jy3Cxk

animal.description:
Meet Precious! This super precious girl is a (a little over) 2 year old Shepard / hound mix who is the biggest cuddle bug you can imagine! She's always trying to get more cuddles, and can never get enough ear scratches! Her foster parents describe her as a very relaxed cuddle bug, whose favorite activities including napping, food, and lots of love. 

Precious is almost completely house trained, working on her leash skills and is very food motivated. This cutie needs to be an only dog and with a family that will work on her reactiveness toward other dogs. She is terrified of other dogs and would do best in a quiet neighborhood. Her trainer believes she was a bait dog before being saved. If you're looking for a one of kind dog who will truly be your best friend, apply to adopt her now!

Precious has recently completed her heart worm treatment and all costs were  covered by us!

If you are interested in adopting, Please Read Below.

Do not email through Petfinder because we won't be able to answer. Please email adopt.truenorthrescue@gmail.com to check on the status of your application. All applications can take anywhere from 24-72 hours to be processed and only approved applicants will be contacted.

If a dog is listed here on Petfinder, they are still available. Please don't email just to ask if they're available - they are! With the high volume of emails we receive daily, it is not guaranteed that we can reply to every inquiry. As a fully volunteer run rescue, we make every effort to reply in a timely fashion, but please allow 24-48 hours for a response.

We strive to have accurate and up to date bios, and regularly check in with our fosters to ensure we are providing the most relevant information. If there is no mention of a health or behavioral concern, then it means we have not been informed of one!

You may read more about our adoption policies and procedures at www.truenorthrescue.org. Please submit a complete application on our website - meet and greets are only scheduled with approved applicants. Please be sure to answer every question as thoughtfully as you can, this will help your chances. Incomplete applications will not be reviewed, and we unfortunately can not contact all applicants to inquire about missing information.

We do not have a public shelter, all of our dogs are in private foster homes. Applications are processed in the order in which they are received. You can email adopt.truenorthrescue@gmail.com for more information.

Think this dog is the one for you? Apply today at www.truenorthrescue.org.

animal.description:
Mr. Opie is 7 years old.  He apparently has been tossed around a lot in the past few months.  He was with an original owner for several years who could no longer keep him.  He got given away and the person who got him  only kept him for two days.  Then that person gave him to another person who let him run free and he got picked up by a police department.  They had him for a very short time and then were seen dumping him out of a truck.  As you can see it has been a while for this guy to get any real love.

We have done his vetting and he is now ready to go home.  He is neutered, current on his shots, wormed, heartworm negative and micro-chipped.  He just needs a committed owner who doesn't dump him or get rid of him.

He loves people - would recommend no children under 12..  He doesn't seem to have ever met a stranger.  We were told he is a "handful" - but most dogs are.  Our guess would be with a little love and attention he will settle in to be a great dog.  His original owner says he is a Mountain Cur.  He is NOT good with cats (or any small creature).

His adoption fee is $125.00.  In order to meet him or visit the shelter you have to submit an application and have that tentatively approved.  You will find the application on our website at www.patriotsforpets.com under the 'Adoption\ tab.

animal.description:
Have you met Tessa?

Tessa was originally surrendered to the San Diego Humane Society-Escondido in August 2020, because her family moved and did not include her in their plans to take her along. Then she was adopted from Frosted Faces, and now she is back, due to no fault of her own. She is 9 years old, weighs 12 lbs., and needs a forever family!

Tessa went on a two week Frosted Fling over the holidays, and we learned so much about what she's like in a home environment. Here's what we know:

Tessa loves mealtime! There were six other dogs in her Fling home, and she was not food aggressive with the other dogs eating around her and did not attempt to go to other bowls once the other dogs were eating. According to her Fling Mom, Tessa integrated well with the rest of the pack. She occasionally became snippy if she was laying with her Fling Mom, and another dog jumped up next to them, but once everyone was laying down, Tessa was fine with sharing her and the space around her.

Tessa does have energy, and despite having a cast for broken toes during the first half of her Fling, she got around with no problem. She became even more agile when the cast came off, but her activity needed to be limited and didn't include walks, which she enjoys. Tessa played with toys a few times during her Fling and also chased her Fling sibling around the yard. Now that she's no longer restricted from activity, we can see Tessa being ready for all kinds of fun with her forever family!

Tessa knows to go potty outside and only had a few accidents in the house, before catching on to using the puppy pad if she needed to. Her Fling Mom learned it was best for Tessa to go outside immediately after eating.

Tessa is a very friendly girl and approached everyone who visited her Fling home hoping to be petted. Tessa was very calm around her Fling Mom's small grandsons. Even with their running around, she was completely at ease. As Tessa became more comfortable in her Fling home, she started sleeping with her Fling Mom at night, snuggled up against her.

She is a sweet girl who asks for very little other than to be loved.

Tessa is now living in a Foster home while she waits for her Forever Family. Might that be you?

Apply to meet her:
www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit during Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/24/21 KG

animal.description:
Meet Mack!  This two-year-old Labrador/Pit mix is a show stopper and handsome boy.  He has a big ole block head and is a solid sixty pounds.  Under all that beefcake, Mack is a loving sweet dog with a gentle disposition.  He is a friend to all and a wonderful family companion.  Mack is great with children and fun to be around.  He enjoys morning walks to see what the neighbors are up to, followed by a good hearty breakfast.  After that, it’s playtime with the kiddos chasing balls or tugging on a toy.  He loves to learn new tricks and is quite bright.  Especially if you throw him a treat!  Mack also is good with other dogs and makes friends easily.  He’s a rough and tumble player with his pals.  A fenced in yard will give him a safe place to run and play.  After a good workout, he likes to unwind with a favorite chew toy.  He calms down quickly and is well mannered in the home.  He is already housebroken, so you can skip the dreaded potty training.  He sleeps well in his own bed but wouldn’t mind being your sleep buddy.  He won’t hog the bed and promises not to snore.  Mack is a pretty chill dude and a fun family dog to have around.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

 I will come (Neutered, current on vaccines, micro chipped, fecal, heart worm tested if age appropriate, monthly flea and tick prevented, dental if recommended by our vet.
Stretch is a 1 year old, 50 pound, hound mix who has such a sad story to share. Stretch was bought as a puppy and just left outside. He was surrendered to a local shelter where he tested positive for Lyme disease. We were asked to help. Of course we couldn’t say no! Stretch finished out his treatment for Lyme disease in a warm, cozy foster home! We found out that Stretch is visually impaired, but that doesn’t stop him from finding his way around! His foster home has stairs and he has mastered them! He knows exactly where the fence line is in the yard, and often enjoys sniffing up and down the fence. Stretch didn’t even know what a toy or treat was when he got to his foster home. Now, he enjoys playing with toys and definitely loves treats!! Stretch is in a foster home with kiddos, cats and dogs. He LOVES new people! Stretch really enjoys snuggling up on the couch with his humans. He is a very laid back boy! 
Adoption fee is $200 and includes his neuter, microchip with registration, UTD on shots and current on heartworm, flea and tick prevention. To apply for Stretch, visit our website https://sianimalrescue.org!

He's doing great in his foster home. The 1st night he marked two things, but after a stern "NO", he hasn't marked anything else. He needs a home with no cats and a 6ft fence. He is starting to try to play with the other dogs in his foster home too. He does sleep through the night in his kennel, but he would love to share your bed with you. He is definitely a lap dog, and he gives hugs too. Watch for him to have his treatment completed, so he can be available for you to adopt!

Please visit www.handsheartspaws.org for an adoption application

All of our dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, fecal tested, heartworm tested, and they are all on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.

The adoption process is an application, a vet reference, a home visit, and a lifetime contract. The requested adoption donation for this dog is $350__.

We do not REQUIRE a fenced in yard (some dogs DO REQUIRE a fence.  Decide what is best for each dog), we do REQUIRE a means of safe outside containment.  We do NOT adopt to homes that use invisible fencing.  Invisible fencing is NOT a safe means of outside containment.

We are willing to adopt out-of-state, contingent on our ability to complete a home visit, but you must travel to Omaha to complete the adoption. We do not transport or ship our dogs.

animal.description:
If you are looking for a super handsome, personable young pup…look no further! Max is here!

Max is a very energetic boy, believed to be a Lab-Great Dane Mix, possibly a bit of Pitbull too!
He’s about a year old, and typical of Labs or Pitbulls of this age, he’s full of energy and can be a challenge to those trying to train him. It’s not his fault though.

Max found himself at Chicago Animal Control when his family no longer wanted him. It is very obvious they never spent any time with him, and certainly never put any effort into training him with even the most basic of commands. So, he arrived at our Safe House, somewhat of a “wild child!”  The good news is however, that Max is eager to please, and is a quick learner. He just needs someone to pay attention to him, work with him, and help him evolve into a perfect family member!

The ideal family for Max is one with extensive dog experience with high-energy dogs, a fenced yard for Max to run and play, possibly a canine companion  of comparable size, and most importantly the time and commitment to Max’s care and training. Due to his current lack of manners and bubbly personality, Max should not be placed in a home with children under the age of 12. He is not at all aggressive but is strong and relatively large (65 or so lbs) and could easily knock over a small person.  Obedience training is required to ensure Max will develop into a well-behaved canine companion.

Max is fully vetted, neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative and on year-round heartworm preventative.

If you are interested in adding this handsome personable pup to your family, and meet the requirements noted, feel free to contact BAARKDogRescue@gmail.com or 847-852-0895.
