animal.description:
Currently in foster in Puyallup, Washington. Lobo was a drop-off out in the country. Heaven only knows why. He is a Lab mix (about 60#s) and very friendly and a bit rambunctious. Judging an energy level from 1-10 (1 is the old Hound Dog; 10 is the Jack Russell that is like the Energy Bunny)... he is about a 7-8. I believe with exercise and training, he will settle down... most of the time. He has not had any training but he's very happy. We think he is about 4 yrs old. He was very skinny but is doing fabulous. He is a higher energy dog and you would think he was 1 not about four! lol

 

Children: Lobo is great with children but because of his high energy level, I wouldn't have him around young children. They need to be at least 12 or older. He will be a good partner for hiking, swimming, bicycling ...(you, not him), etc.

 

Cats: He does chase cats. Must be in a cat-less house or at least keep them totally separate.

Heartworm Tested: He is HEART WORM NEG.

 

House Training: We believe he has been an outside dog most of his life. Along with the behavior training, potty training should be easy because he's never known he could do his business in the house. It's just a matter of bonding and communicating.

 

Adoptions include neuter/spay, vaccinations (DHPP, Bordetella, Rabies), microchip, transport with one of our professional dog transporters, and 6 mos of heartworm prevention..

 

If you have any questions, text me... 210-394-6060.

 

Lobo is available for pre-adoption. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out the on-line application. COPY and PASTE the application link .

http://shaynesrescue.com/adoption-application-pet-central-satx/

 

You can also go to our Facebook page...

https://www.facebook.com/Pet-Central-SATX-866684826744181/

and LIKE us to help us out.

 

GET IN LINE FIRST: If you are interested in this dog, please fill out the application (link listed above). The rescue will contact you once the application is received. Although we strive to answer everyone, due to the high volume of inquiries we receive, we cannot guarantee a response to all emails. Filling out the application is the ONLY way to ensure a response from the rescue. In addition, while you are emailing us, if others apply, you lose out adopting the dog you chose. We have hundreds of puppies/dogs available so there really is no need to apply anywhere else. Also, one application is good even if you are interested in several different dogs...one application no matter which one you choose. We try to make it as easy as possible for you but if you are applying or have applied anywhere else, we do need to know that, too.

 

SHANYE'S FOSTERS is a group of foster parents in the Olympia/Tumwater area. We foster dogs for rescues and assist them in adopting/rehoming of their pups/dogs by listing on this site. Many dogs posted here are available to pre adopt NOW directly from the rescue. The only ones in foster in the NW specifically state that. We have very few fosters so most need to be pre adopted. All adoption fees go towards rescuing more dogs in need. No one receives a salary. Shayne's Fosters is not responsible for any experience you have with any dog you might see posted on this site. They are the property of the sponsoring rescue who will supply all medical supporting records which is given with each dog when adopted.

 

Our adoption fees cover all medical costs to make sure the pups are appropriately vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and spayed/ neutered. It also covers the cost of transport from Texas and the necessary health certificate documentation. The fees also include a negative heartworm test for any dogs over 6 months. Some dogs have additional medical, such as FHO, ACL, hernias, dental, and a myriad of other vetting. We do full disclosure of medical care/situations. If the adoption fees seem high (which never cover the true cost of rescue), we recommend fostering for a good rescue. Fostering ensures you incur no vet bills and no boarding fees. We are always in need of good fosters. We are all volunteers who donate our time and resources to help save as many dogs/pups lives as we possibly can.

 

Thank you for choosing to adopt a rescue pup/dog. Over 1 billion dogs worldwide are put to sleep (PTS) annually... thousands daily. The dog pounds PTS entire litters, pregnant/nursing moms and wonderful dogs that can make someone a great companion. We firmly believe there is NO breed other than "rescue" for all species. Thank you for being part of the village it takes to save these precious lives.

Like a little sugar with your coffee?

PERFECT, I'm your gal. Nice to meet you, I'm Coffee. They say I'm sweet as can be. I love all the people and even give kisses to prove it! My foster mom calls me a chonker and tells me I'm down with the thickness. I don't know what she means but we're working on it. My happy place is in my big, soft, fluffy dog bed! You know what they say, the one who snores will fall asleep first and I'm a gold medalist. If you have any doggie friends at home, I'd love to meet them! I'm a pretty chill gal, but I still love to play! My squeaky tennis ball is my most favorite toy, and I really like when my foster mom zoomies around the house with me.

I've never been one for the fast life though, I enjoy my walks nice and slow so I can take in the view and smell the roses. I take treats very gentle and have the cutest toots a girl could have. I let you know when I need to use the ladies room, or when I'm out of water and I always do it with a big smile on my face. So, what do ya say? Wanna chill, hang out, watch movie, play tag and maybe even just catch some Z's? 

Love is in the air, and it smells like COFFEE.

I am currently in a foster home. Please email: foster@kcpetproject.org to meet me!

My name is Ting Ting I am an 8 to 10 month old German Shepherd/lab mix girl who weighs about 45lbs. My life was not always great, my owners were about to move off and leave me behind when the nice rescue lady took me in. I never knew what shelter was other than under a mobile home. They said I was heartworm negative and the rescue people were so glad and put me on preventative to keep me that way. I am a very sweet girl that is shy at first but loves to snuggle. My foster mommy tells me I am a very smart gal because I learned the doggie door like a pro and the crate training thing was a breeze. Can you give a great gal like me a furever home to call my own? I promise lots of snuggles and unconditional love abounding.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Reeci! I was surrendered by my owner to Big Dog Ranch Rescue, along with my sister Alaska, after our owner passed away. We are bonded and it would be best for both of us if we could be adopted together. I am a sweet girl but very vocal and sometimes you might mistake those sounds as me being angry but I'm really not. I like to play with other dogs, but I can be selective with who I choose to engage with. As a Husky, I most likely have a high prey drive and would probably prefer not to be in a home with cats or other small animals. I would ABSOLUTELY LOVE if I could find an experienced Husky owner who is aware of our high energy levels, large size, and high-maintenance grooming needs (I need to be brushed daily!) I would love a great big yard for me to run around in and I think I'd be happiest living a rather quiet lifestyle with my new family. I can be a bit protective of my territory so it's best to go slow with me and let me warm up to you. I am most protective of my food and will become quiet vocal during mealtimes which may sound mean, but again, I am really a true sweetheart! I do require additional training, again I am VERY vocal, but I do appear to be potty trained and love to go for long leashed walks.

animal.description:
Oh sweet sweet boy- Winston where were you before here? I can tell you are a little afraid we will hurt you but you never show us any defense.... you just cower down when we reach out until you realize our touch is soft and you warmly lean into it. When I see you relax like that my heart melts. You have been so good for crate rest even though it stinks for a young dog. You rarely bark anymore or have an accident. I think you understand we had to save your life in more ways then one. We found you had heart worms when we rescued you and had you treated so your body needs to rest. We’d love to find a real family for you to be with while you finish crate rest and then slowly get to bloom into the dog you were always meant to be.  We are looking my dear boy. I know you thought you were safe when the kind old man in Danville Arkansas took you in- it was supposed to be a life long sanctuary.... but he died. It didn’t help that he had 30 of you living isolated on his property and this whole world seems so big and loud now. I know you were scared and sick but you never have to be scared again because we love you and will take care of you. We will find a warm and loving family, one with a spacious home and lots of soft places to lay. Tons of toys to toss and chew. And people who appreciate what an angel boy you are! Don’t worry buddy - I will find them. They are out there looking for you and don’t even know it yet. But they are waiting for you and you will complete their family. 

Winston deserves the nicest family for the nicest dog. He can jump fences so he can’t go to a family that wants to be able to leave him play in the yard. He loves everyone. He loves toys. He’s easily startled but is gaining confidence everyday. Winston needs another dog to take cues from and wilts when he is alone! So you MUST have another friendly dog to be Winstons best friend and guide!

Musts:
Have another dog
Accept he can jump fences and not leave him alone
Patience for a shy dog
Children over 10
Wants:
Calmer household
Experience with anxiety/nervousness

Winstons fee is $800 and includes his heartworm treatment and all of our regular package of course!

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Winston is a gentle sweet soul who is a touch shy. Still very playful! He loves toys and other dogs! Great with cats. He is good with older children. Say 10or 12 or older?. Little ones just make him nervous and barky.

Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
Nutmeg Spice is about 6 years old, although she acts younger. She is a bigger dachshund mix at 20lbs. She has short red fur. She was found on the streets in San Antonio and was given all her vaccines at the S.A. ACS and is heartworm negative. She was spayed also.

The day she was taken out of the shelter and brought to her foster home, Nutmeg was very shy. It took a little while before she was comfortable.

Now she is playful, loves toys!! She doesn't like sharing her toys though. She loves playing with the fosters dogs and can play for a very long time. She and the other dogs seem to like playing tag!

Nutmeg wants to be beside you wherever you go! She will chew her toys on top of your feet!! If you sit down, she will be on your lap and giving kisses and just loves hugs!!

Nutmeg would love a playmate but if she would be the only dog, she could get use to that, especially if you are there for most of the day.

While under our care, Nutmeg started having a couple of seizures. We got her into the vet and she is now on seizure meds and she is doing great, no more seizures. She is ready for adoption. If you want a great dog to love and don't mind giving her medicine, then she could be a good dog for you!

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Zella has never met a stranger. She has expressive Yota-like ears and is a curious, gentle, and loving girl. A friend to all. Zella is proud of her toys - she loves toys! - and will show you her many talents. She learns new commands very quickly. She is both cute and one smart cookie!

Zella has a good balance of independence and a desire for human attention, with her first choice being cuddles and petting. She would love a home where she could have a dog sibling who also likes to run and play, but that is not an absolute requirement, as long as she has people to play with her. In addition to a regular, daily walk schedule, Zella does need ample time each day to run and explore freely. For this reason, she will be happiest in a home with a securely fenced yard to play in safely.

Zella is crate trained and house trained. She is looking forward to meeting her new forever family.

animal.description: Say Hello to the Idyllwild Pups! These little Labrador Retriever mixes are the sweetest pups ever. They are around 2 months old and looking for families to play with, explore with, cuddle with, and love! They were born in a foster home where they received the very best care and lots of love. Their beautiful, sweet mama, Idyllwild, is on the medium to large side at about 40 lbs. We don't know dad or what exactly these pups are mixed with so are guessing that these cuties will grow up to be medium to large sized dogs like mom. Cove is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. We require all puppy adopters to provide training that includes: house training, basic training, leash training, and socialization. Additionally, this cutie is going to need proper exercise, mental stimulation, and your attention and love to grow up to be the best companion. We do not allow our dogs or puppies to sleep or live outside; they must be incorporated into your family and be made a priority in your life. In return, you will have the most loving and loyal family member you could ask for. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting a puppy, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! Please note that processing time for applications is currently three to four weeks. We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description: Hello there, my name is Lily. I'm currently residing off site, getting some much needed R&R. Life as a shelter pup can be stressful and we all need some ""me"" time every now and then. The staff at Nuzzles has learned lots about me, and what they've found is that I'm a picky girl who needs a very specific home. The thing is, I didn't live the best life before coming to Nuzzles, so I'm very leery of strangers. Sometimes I just hang my head and try to avoid them and other times I try and scare them away by barking. I feel misunderstood a lot of the time, and will need an owner who is patient, kind, and gentle. I need a quiet home with just one to two people who will be committed to following my behavior modification plan. I'm ""dog selective"" meaning I keep a tight circle of friends, so another dog isn't necessarily a deal breaker, but we definitely need to do a meet and greet before adoption. I've been working really hard becoming my best self, but certain things are deal breakers for me. First is cats. To me, they look like toys and I just don't understand why everyone keeps telling me I can't chase them! Second is children. They are small, loud, and move way too quickly for my taste. I know I've got some quirks, and that I'm not the dog for everybody but I still dream of having a family to call my own. If you would like to learn more about me, please fill out an application so we can get to know each other better.

animal.description:
Bean is a male mixed breed puppy.

Breed is totally unknown mom is small at 15lb however it seems daddy could have been a large breed based on the puppies growth paterns.

We are reviewing apps at this time but have not yet choosen their homes.

Because we do not know their DNA make up this means they could be 30lbs or 60 or more lbs as adults we really do not know so please keep this in mind if you are looking for a certain sized dog. 

They are young puppies only just born in Nov. this means they are not yet house trained and will require a lot of training to grow into wonderful happy companions.

Puppies require a great deal of time and interactions please be sure your lifestyle is fit for a young puppy, prior to applying.

They are good with cats dogs and kids.

Please refrain from asking questions until your application has been approved at that time we are happy to answer all questions.

We will not be doing meet and greets. And we only meet with approved adopters currently with the current world state being what it is.

Thank you for choosing adoption!

animal.description: Levi Strauss is the full package: athletic, playful and oh so handsome. If you're looking for the best of both worlds - a quiet homebody and an adventurous trail buddy - this big, beautiful dog is for you! Levi's idea of the perfect day involves going on long walks or hikes where he can sniff the good scents, and maybe even take a little dip in the water. Later on, he'd like to jump in the car (where he's always on his best behavior) for a burger at P. Terry's drive-thru. Then he would love to cap it off with a nice long nap on the couch. After he gets his second wind, Levi's ready to play fetch in the play yard or soak in the kiddie pool. At home, Levi prefers the quiet companionship of his person. This sensitive pup needs a low traffic lifestyle without many visitors. He's house-trained, and has been left free roam without a problem. He's just as comfortable being in the crate, and will sometimes even bring his toys in there to play. Levi figures out the rules of the house quickly, such as being allowed on the couch for snuggles, but not the bed. He's also working on his skills with his TOP (Total Obedience Program) trainer. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 Are you ready to bring home a new best friend who will stay by your side through thick and thin? Levi Strauss is your guy! Follow Levi Strauss on Instagram @adopt_levi_strauss

Hi friends! My name is Spencer!  

Apparently my new foster family says I’m the sweetest most gentle soul.  I just know that I love everyone and everything I meet. 
*insert puppy shrug here *

I love dogs. I love cats. I love kids. I love old folks.  Heck! I even love grumpy, overwhelmed middle aged women!  I give lots of snuggles and tail wags to help them all. 

I walk beautifully on a leash. I never bark. I LOVE getting back scratches from anyone and anything. You name it- I’ll ask it to scratch me. I’m housetrained and go easily into my crate (when properly bribed, of course!) , and I still have enough pep in my step to run with my human foster brother. 
I may have a bit of gray in my beard,  but I have a lot of love to give and life to enjoy. I’ll be finding my forever family soon and I can’t wait! 

To adopt me you can visit the website at rescueapittie.org to fill out an application online.

animal.description:
NAME: Ace
BREED: Schnauzer/Poodle Mix
BIRTHDAY: 2006
WEIGHT: 20lbs
ADOPTION FEE: $200

Ace is a cute dog. His paperwork says he's a Yorkie/Poodle Mix but we definitely see Schnauzer in that wiry hair and square face. He's a great size; small enough to be carried but not small enough to be stepped on. His tail is a little nub and his ears are nothing but goofy.

Ace is a sweet dog. He gets along great with other dogs and cats and has no issues with aggression or resource guarding. He loves curling up in a bed or a pile of blankets and he doesn't even snore. He rides well in the car and is a very quiet fellow. Ace believes that mealtime should be all the time and gets super excited when it's time for food. He's not a picky eater and enjoys both dry and canned foods.

Ace is an old dog. He takes medications for his joints but does have some weakening of his back end. He is full of lumps and bumps, doesn't see or hear well, and gets confused easily. Offering Ace a treat is a dangerous task, as he sometimes mistakes your fingers for the treat and chomps hard. He likes to go outside and is happy to potty out there, but he also has plenty of accidents in the house and is not consistent with a pee pad. Wandering around throughout the day and into the night sometimes leads Ace through his accidents and makes a bigger mess, but he doesn't notice so he's not sorry. Offering Ace a pat on the head confuses him and makes him nervous, but he likes body scratches once he figures out what's going on.

Ace is not a dog for everyone. He can not live with small children or with someone who will not have patience for his quirks and age-related issues. But he is a good boy and we are committed to finding him a real home! Ace is neutered, current on vaccines, heartworm negative, and had a dental cleaning 12/8. His bloodwork was normal.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Any that he can't step on accidentally

animal.description: Hi! My name is Phoebe and I am 4 month old red heeler.  I was picked up as a stray by a local animal shelter with broken leg.  Luckily Herding Haven took me into rescue and fixed my leg.  I had to wear a cast and "rest" for what seemed like an eternity (my foster mom says it was only a couple of weeks), but that's like 6 months in dog years! Don't let my serious pictures fool you;  I'm a happy-go-lucky,  spunky little red head.  I love to play with other dogs, go for walks and chase frisbees. I'm a sock thief (but, I don't chew them) and a cuddle bug.  I love attention and show my happiness with little "snorts" of joy (my foster mom things I am part piglet!). animal.description:
Senior Hearts Rescue and Renewal is the only licensed senior dog rescue organization in Western Pennsylvania. We do not have a shelter or a public facility. ALL of our dogs reside in foster homes in the greater Pittsburgh, PA area. 

We are a 100% volunteer organization. Please respect our volunteers' time. If a dog is listed on PetFinder, he/she IS available for adoption. We cannot reply to messages, phone calls, and emails about a dog until we have received, reviewed, and approved an adoption application. 

Our ADOPTION application is found at www.seniorhearts.org Completing this application is the first step in our adoption screening process. You MUST complete the application in its entirety in order to be considered as a potential adopter.  Please select "More About Us" for further details on our adoption requirements.  You can meet a dog ONLY after we have completed our adoption approval process.

If you are looking at the dog below, it most certainly means the dog is available for adoption. We look forward to receiving your application in hopes that you are able to meet our adoption requirements and provide this dog with a loving furever home.

A little about Noella...
 I weigh 14 pounds and am ONLY 7 years young...not your usual senior. I am healthy and active. In fact I am VERY active. I love playing with humans and toys. Tug of war is my favorite game. I especially love being outdoors and going on long walks.  The more walks the better for me.

I am vision impaired. But it certainly doesn't bother me. Sure I need carried up and down stairs. But I don't weigh much. I am house trained and crate trained. I am in good health too.

I get along with all dogs and I dont mind cats. In facts I like dogs so much that I require a dog sibling in my furever home. We can play together and cause quite a ruckus! 

I could be adopted into a family with older repectful children or I'd be a great companion for someone who just wanted to have fun.

If you are looking for a young senior dog with a little spunk then I am your girl.  I can be adopted within a two-hour radius of Pittsburgh, PA. If you are interested in giving me a furever home, you must first complete the adoption application at www.seniorhearts.org

Please note we are unable to respond to any inquiries about a listing. If a dog is listed here she is available for adoption. If you are interested in her you must FIRST complete an adoption application at www.seniorhearts.org

animal.description:
Jenny’s not the type to come to your house and help herself to a glass of water--she’s a quiet and polite houseguest, mostly preferring to hang in her crate during the day and then cuddle up on the couch for a movie night. That’s how Jenny prefers things for a while--she needs some time to feel at home. Her foster mom says slowly, but surely, Jenny is showing the dog that is inside of her: “Even though she’s shy, I know she’s in a good mood when she wiggles or hops up onto the couch enthusiastically!” 

A patient family that’s willing to play the long game when it comes to bringing Jenny out of her shell would suit her perfectly--the sights and sounds of the world are still pretty scary to her, so having your steadfast support through it all (and your couch snuggs at night) is all she asks for! She’s got a mellow energy, so she’s happy to stick around the house and yard to keep things low key until she builds the courage to take on more of the world.

An important note Jenny wanted to make sure we included is that she is a big fan of peanut butter, cheese, and perked up significantly with take out from Dave’s Hot Chicken entered the house. She may be a bit of a DoorDash aficionado and would happily help you select the most delicious smelling dinners Los Angeles has to offer!

Jenny would prefer to be your only dog at home, but could potentially live with a feline friend with a proper introduction.

About 3 years old and 50 pounds, Jenny is crate-trained, house-trained, micro-chipped, up to date on routine vaccinations and knows her basic commands.

animal.description:
DEAFAudi
6 yo female
Deaf
White
65 pounds
Older Kid Friendly
Dog Friendly w/ Slow intros
Leash & Crate Trained
Medication Needs
fostered in Olympia, Wa

Hey ya'll! I'm Audi. Yep, just like the luxury car....zoom zoom!! I'm around 5 and a half years old (a lady never tells her age, right?) and I am SPECIAL!

What does that mean, you wonder? Well, it means that I am deaf - but no way do I let that slow me down. These days, I feel like I could run to the moon and back - and that makes me so happy cuz I was pretty under the weather when I joined the ranks of NWBR several months ago. But thanks to their committed dedication and my foster family's love and care, I am doing SO much better and I feel great. I do have some medication to take for the rest of my life but it's nothing scary or complicated & I think it's kinda cool, actually - cuz I get peanut butter or cheese every day now. Woo hoo!! Score!! Anyway, back to the "about me" show...

Because I cannot hear, I am a bit of a "shadow" pup - meaning I feel a LOT more secure when I am with my people. So, yes, I will definitely follow you to the bathroom, outside, to the kitchen.....you name it, I am there! But I promise not to get in the way - I just like to see you, it makes me feel safe. Speaking of which, if you have to leave the house for a while, I am happy to curl up in my crate with a nice blankie and some classical opera or 70's funk to listen to. (It helps me get my meditation on.) Because I am super smart, I could totally learn hand signals if someone wants to teach me some, but I promise I really am just like other dogs and you don't have to be scared of adopting me just because I cannot hear. I am a great best friend! In fact, having another fur friend in my forever home would be awesome too - I live with a big and a small one in my foster home, and I was kind of nervous about them at first, but they are totally my peeps now! They taught me about toys - which are so cool, and playing - which I love to do. I love a good walk or romp in a good sized back yard, and I am learning that the world is a wonderfully interesting place to do zoomies in. Human kiddos are ok with me, though I prefer the ones who are bit older. Not because I don't like the little ones - I love all people!! It's just because the littles are super bouncy and holy moly, do they move really fast sometimes! Because I am deaf, that kinda makes me a little nervous.

So, now that you know more about me, would you be interested in giving me a chance to show you how much I can love you? I have been hanging out with my foster family for quite a while, and I am having a great time here - but I feel in my bones that a special forever family is out there just waiting for me to call my own!

Interested in adopting Audi? Fill out the application here:

https://www.nwboxerrescue.org/adoption-form

If you would like to adopt her, fill out an adoption application on our website www.nwboxerrescue.org

Like us on facebook for more photos of this pretty girl, as well as other boxers we have available! www.facebook.com/northwestboxerrescue

***ADOPTION PENDING***

PLEASE READ THIS PROFILE AND THE REQUESTED CRITERIA BEFORE CALLING OR SUBMITTING AN APPLICATION. THANKS FOR YOUR ATTENTION AND CONSIDERATION 

MEET ARTIE….a cutie patootie 6-7 yr old, 9.5 lb (underweight, should be 10-11 lbs), cream/tan, Shih Tzu boy, who came from the East Valley Shelter, suspected of being hit by a car.  The only thing our vet could tell was that Artie had very dirty teeth and was matted (and smelly) to the bone!  His teeth have been cleaned, he’s had his makeover and he’s been given two thumbs up!! 

If you look closely, Artie has one blue eye…very unusual!  Even though his coat was a mess, we could tell that when you let it grow out, it will be very pretty (if groomed and kept up!)  Artie is a sweetheart who is very quiet and curious and we believe he was loved at some time.  We can tell you he isn’t quite potty trained, but if kept on a schedule, he’s getting better.  We have yet to hear him bark, so no worries there.   

We have gotten to know Artie better and he is still coming out of his shell.  He is asking for attention, follows us around and LOVES to be rubbed…esp his ears and head!  He likes squeaky toys, but isn’t sure what to do with them!  Finally, he is curious and wants to engage with the other dogs but they could care less…but another interested dog in the home who is small and friendly would be best for little Artie because he does not like being left alone.    He is probably fine with kids, since he has no aggression.  A home where he will get oodles of attention and love is the home where Artie should be!!  Does that sound like yours?

Our website is updated daily. Please do not apply for this dog unless your home fits the specified criteria. All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, groomed, vet checked, dewormed, deflea'd and come with a leash, collar and ID If you are interested in adopting this dog from Lhasa Happy Homes, please complete the adoption application via the link below: Adoption (Online) Application: https://lhasahappyhomes.org/adoptions/adoption-application/. We will contact you once it has been reviewed. 

During the COVID-19 quarantine, Lhasa Happy Homes will NOT be holding weekly adoption events. We will set up individual meet & greets with APPROVED applicants once they have submitted a video tour of their home. 

You can check our Events Calendar at http://www.lhasahappyhomes.org/HLM_Custom_Calendar.aspx.

Thanks for thinking rescue and adoption…and for considering saving a life. It will be the best gift you ever give yourself or your family.

animal.description:
ADOPT ME ONLINE: https://ophrescue.org/dogs/9245

My name is English Spot. I think I am a little over 4 years old and weigh around 50 lbs. I am quiet and housebroken in my fosters home. I like other dogs and cats but don't really know how to play with them so I ignore them. I am at my happiest when on the move as is evident in the videos below. True to hound dog behavior I like to explore and will wander off if left alone and not come back on my own. So an ideal home for me would be with an active individual or family with older dog-savvy kids, a fenced yard and another dog who is willing to teach me how to trust, play, and relax. It will take me sometime to build a relationship of trust so I hope my future person is very patient with me. I am a low maintenance, low to medium energy dog but still need to stretch my long legs and get exercise. You can see how much I love to run in the 3rd video.

Click here and here to see more. .

Click here and here to see him in action!

This is what we do know about English Spot: 

He is crate trained. 
Walks very well on a leash.
He ran a 5k with 100+ other dogs and was in his element.
He's a very lovable dog, not a mean bone in his body.
He loves to sit on the couch with his human foster brother. 
He came into a Virginia shelter as a stray with some head wounds. 
Was treated for heartworm.
He is a creature of habit and is sensitive to change. 
Because he is shy, he likes to hide and put himself in corners. 
He will not seek your affection but when hes relaxed in his environment he will follow your movements with his eyes. 
He doesn't play with his 4-legged foster siblings but we see glimpses of a desire to learn. 
Hes looking for that perfect active person who is willing to be patient and understanding with him. 

If you feel that English Spot is a dog you could love knowing that he will require a lot of patience, proactive energy and time then please apply to adopt at www.OPHrescue.org.

To adopt this dog, or any OPH dog, fill out the simple online application at https://ophrescue.org 
Operation Paws for Homes, Inc. (OPH) rescues dogs of all breeds and ages from high-kill shelters in NC, VA, MD, and SC, reducing the numbers being euthanized. With limited resources, the shelters are forced to put down 50-90% of the animals that come in the front door. OPH provides pet adoption services to families located in VA, DC, MD, PA and neighboring states. OPH is a 501(c)(3) organization and is 100% donor funded. OPH does not operate a shelter or have a physical location. We rely on foster families who open their homes to give love and attention to each dog before finding a forever home.

I just arrived to ODHS but the humans promised to update my bio as they learn more about me! 

You can still come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards. ail you back.

As a puppy, I am required to go to training within 90 days of my adoption with a certified trainer. Paws and Heels is recommended. 

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturday from 12-2. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt.

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer

Crackers was originally part of a hoarding situation in the Tulsa area. The lady turned many dogs over to local rescues, but was allowed to keep 4 dogs. Snowbell and Crackers were two of the dogs that she kept. Unfortunatly a year later she passed away. The dogs then found themselves at Tulsa Animal Welfare. A foster family took the chihuahuas in to get them out of the shelter. They then came here to ARF. Snowbell is still nervous, but is a sweet dog. Her and Crackers are bonded and we would love for them to be adopted together.

Fill out an application at the link below. Find the dog/cat you are interested in and click the adopt button. That will take you to an application. Once approved you will be called for an appointment to meet your possible new family member, or at that time you can meet the other animals as well. https://petstablished.com/public/search/shelter/301551

Adoption fee is $150 which includes, spay/neuter, vaccines, etc, and a free 1 year membership to our 5 acre ARF Park. For other dog questions please email ARFdogs74006@gmail.com

We do adopt out of state, but the adopter must travel to ARF to meet the dog they are looking to adopt. They must have an approved application before traveling to meet the dog. We do allow small dogs that are eligible to fly in the cabin of a plane. We DO NOT allow dogs to travel in the cargo area of the plane under any circumstances. Any dog that is adopted can of course go by personal vehicle. We do not allow dogs to be transported "pony express style" where they are passed from driver to driver.

Suspected Breed(s): Foxhound
Gender: Male
Age: 2 years old
Weight: 58 lbs
Personality: adventurous, smart, energetic, goofy, friendly, gentle, easygoing, playful, calm, quick learner, adaptable, outgoing, quiet
Observations with Dogs: Generally good with other dogs. Playful towards other dogs in the foster or other people's homes. He LOVES saying hi, so does often pull on the leash toward other dogs while out on walks.
Observations with Cats: Untested
Observations with Kids: Untested
House Training Progress: No recent accidents.
Crate Training Progress: Does well in crate
Location: DC area foster
Rescued From: Columbus County, NC
Additional Information: Bartlett (Bart for short) is such a sweet boy and will approach you throughout the day for some ear scratches, which are his favorite. He loves long walks but is also content napping during the day as long as he gets a significant amount of exercise first. He is super friendly, and loves to say hello to everyone (humans, kids, dogs). Bartlett can be stubborn during walks, happily trotting where he wants or stopping in his tracks, but he has started to improve with training. Bartlett knows the word sit and is learning the words down, come, and off! This funny boy is sometimes scared to go through doorways, but with a little encouragement, he will go through and return to his happy self. Bartlett loves outings to the dog park, where he runs like a deer! He is a playful boy who needs to burn off his energy.

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster-based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first-served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pitbull Terrier

Gender: Female

Estimated Date of Birth: September 26, 2017

Location: Dallas, Ga

ABOUT BLUEBELLE
Bluebelle found herself at animal control, along with her nine puppies, after her owner called AC on his own dogs when she become protective of her puppies. She remained protective of her puppies at the pound and other rescue groups would not touch an aggressive mom. When they started to get sick, they became urgent; AC was considering separating mom and pups, as other groups would likely take the puppies alone, but that's not how we work. At FTTF, we don't take puppies without the mother. Thankfully, one of our amazing foster homes stepped up to foster the entire family so we were able to bring all ten into FTTF.

By the time we got them, all were all very sick with pneumonia. We rented an oxygen generator and built a chamber for them but, even with around-the-clock care, we lost four pups. However, thanks to the amazing care given by their foster family and everyone at New Hope Animal Hospital, Bluebelle and her five remaining pups fully recovered and continue to show how resilient and incredible they are! Today, they are all thriving. Bluebelle will be available for adoption once she is fully vetted and spayed.

Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and fed premium grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, shots current (DHPP, Bordetella and Rabies where applicable), dewormed, flea and tick treated and microchipped.
* If you are interested in a dog, please first read the biography on the dog (keep scrolling down for the bio!) and then go to our website, www.dpsrescue.com for an application. Our adoption fee is $400-$800. Each biography will specifically list the adoption fee.Adoption Fee: $500
Due to his level of under socialization, we are open to a foster to adopt situation for Jughead.
Jughead is a 1 year old Jack Russell Terrier mix who came to us from a hoarding situation where he and his nine siblings were left in a backyard, and thus emerged super under-socialized. In his foster home, he is slowly learning that people can be trusted, and he has benefitted from the presence of another dog in the home. That said, he still needs a lot of work to learn that he is safe with people. He came into his foster home completely terrified but now enjoys being near his foster mom and has proved to be a great work-from-home companion. On occasion, he has even been known to cuddle.
Jughead can be very loyal once he learns to trust. He enjoys laying near his foster mom and doesn't disturb her meetings. He is happy just as long as he has his blankets to lay on and likes it when you are in one place so he doesn't have to move around. He is really great with other dogs and would make a great playmate for a dog that likes to play. He has shown he can improve with patience, sometimes cuddling his foster mom in bed and letting her pet him. We are very positive that with love and patience he will make a perfect pup.
This is how his foster mom describes his current schedule:
'First thing he does is get up and go to the bathroom with my dogs. He then goes back to bed for about an hour before he gets up again to eat. He likes to play a bit in the am before he settles back down and takes naps with my dogs. He gets up several times a day to go outside then play a little. He does like having a toy to chew on during the day as well. In the afternoon he is the most active and likes romping around with my dogs and taking walks. He naps in the evening and eats his dinner. When he hears us set our house alarm, he knows it is time for bed and runs in our room and jumps on the bed to go to sleep.'
Jughead loves playing with the other two dogs in his foster home and would do best in a home that has other dogs already, thus applicants that have one will be given priority in the interview process.
Jughead is only an option for homes that have had a dog of their own as an adult. Dog sitting and family pets do not count. If there are any children in the home they need to be over the age of ten.

animal.description:
This soulful sweetheart is ready to melt hearts and give kisses! Charlie is a special pup who may not be able to see, but who has a heightened ability to love! As you can imagine, he likes to take in new things at his own pace. He can be a bit shy while he reorients himself in a new environment or around new people, but he will steal your heart (and your couch, if you let him!) in no time. New dogs have made him nervous so far, but it's possible that he may be able to get along with other dogs if introduced slowly. 

Charlie's favorite activities include snuggling up next to his humans and getting gentle face rubs. He's a smart boy who has already acclimated to his crate training, knows to follow on a leash by listening to where you are, and is ready to keep learning more!

Charlie loves to play with toys, and tug of war is his favorite game so far. But give him a blanket and you might be in for a surprise - he loves to rub his face in it and hop around like an excited little bunny. Charlie's endearing quirks have won over the hearts of everyone who has met him - shelter staff, his fosters, and of course his rescue family. If you'd like to be the next heart stolen by Charlie, send in your application!

Charlie is just over a year old, 78 pounds, and ready for his forever home. Visit liveloveanimalrescue.org for an adoption application.

animal.description:
Hutch aka Jackson is bouncy happy guy who has been starved for attention and neglected for too long.  While we don’t know the specifics of his history, we can surmise that he had been an outside dog until he came to us, likely confined to a kennel with a dog house.  He came to us by way of the Perry County Dog Shelter as an unclaimed stray who tested positive for heartworm disease.  He has been in out care for several months now as he underwent treatment for his heartworm disease as well as learning to live like an inside dog and enjoying every day attention and individualized walks.  He is an energetic guy and looks forward to playing in the snow this winter with his new family and then curling up on a new dog bed to dream of all the good things to come.  Hutch is very sweet and loving....  He’s not suited for living with cats and will do best if not exposed to other dogs--he lives with other dogs in his foster home but that was after a very slow controlled introduction..  We are estimating him to be a middle aged (maybe 5-6 ish) dog, likely Lab and another sporting breed mix.  He is approximately 70lbs. Vet reference required  No invisible fence and would do best with a 6 ft privacy fence.

This is a lovely note from a family that kept Hutch for a week, unfortunately he was not a good fit for them but they were hoping this would help him find the right home:

Hutch is very affectionate and loves to sit, sleep,
and walk close to you. He made us think of the
traits of a golden retriever.
We noticed he that he is anxious when separated.
He did not like to be crated but he accepted his
“fate” and joyfully embraced your return. That
might all change once he settles into your home
and knows this is his safe place.
He loves baby carrots and ice cubes for snacks.
He loves to trash pick tissues from open trash cans
and is a counter surfer. House training was easy,
just had to be shown where to go. He paces when
he needs to go outside. He is eager to please so
with training those issues will be eliminated.
We believe he will be best placed in a home with a
fence and no cats. Wait to introduce other dogs.
He LOVES to chase squirrels which is great in the
yard, not so good when walking him. Trainable fix.
Hutch will warm your heart and be a great addition
to any family. He loves children. Avoid balls and
stuffed toys that squeak. He loves to carry them
around but tears up for the squeaker.
Love him and he will return that love 110%.

Adoption fee $150

If you would like to meet Hutch please complete an application for adoption. LINK TO APPLICATION IS BELOW
Copy and paste link into your browser
http://fs17.formsite.com/adoptionscc/form1/index.html


Any vaccinations/boosters due after adoption is finalized will be the new owner's responsibility. All animals are current at time of adoption but in some cases a booster series is required or a vaccine cannot be given due to age and cannot be completed prior to adoption

Our adoptable animals come to us from various sources, the most common being from an animal shelter who is unable to handle their physical or mental needs in the shelter setting but believe with the appropriate care, they can become adoptable. Adoption fees vary based on age, needs and sponsoring.

animal.description:
"Sam I am" as we affectionately call Sam is a staff and volunteer favorite at the shelter.  As you can see by Sam's ears his life hasn't always been pleasant but he tries very hard to be a good mannered boy.  He is affectionate with the volunteers and staff though it does take him time to warm up to new people.  He doesn't like strangers, loud noises, or quick, sudden movements.  Those things trigger something within him from his past that make him uneasy.  Sam would do well in a home without any other pets, no children and an extremely patient and loving adopter.  His adopter needs to remember Sam has had a hard life and deserves only the best, lots of treats, snuggles, and love.  Sam walks very well on the leash and loves to go for his daily walk.   Everyone at the shelter is rooting for this sweet boy to find his forever home.  

For more information, please contact Isle of Wight County Animal Services at 757-365-6318.

animal.description:
**ADOPTION APPLICATION REQUIRED via our website Rarerescue.org**

ADOPTION FEES: Our Adoption Fees vary based on adoptability to help all of the animals in our organization. Please make sure to read the adoption fee below in the bio.

BREEDS: We are not breed experts. The breed(s) listed for each adoptable are best guesses or suggestions.

STEPS TO ADOPT:

Read the adoptable’s bio below, including their adoption fee

Read  ADOPTION PROCESS page under the "Adopt" section

Complete the  DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION (located on our website RARErescue.org)

*Applications will be attended to before general inquiries. We may or may not have time to respond to general inquiries if you have not submitted an application.

We understand that it is important to you to find the right fit for your family. We feel the same way! The application is important and necessary for this reason. 

All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption

BASIC INFORMATION:

Suggested Breed(s): Boxer/Australian Cattle Dog
Gender: Male/Neutered
Approx. Age or D.O.B: Approx 2-3 years
Approx. Weight: 65 lbs
Coat Type: Short
Good around most dogs: Yes
Good around most cats: Yes
Energy Level: Medium
Fence yard may be required: Yes, fenced yard required
Any other specifics:   Check out that face!! Dawson is an adorable guy with a goofy personality and he had so much fun at the Christmas parade we attended last week! 
We're thinking he's a boxer/cattle dog mix from his characteristics, but he thinks he's a lap dog! Dawson needs a fenced yard do play in but he certainly can chill and hang out in the house too. He's great with other dogs and ignores cats. 
Dawson does not like to be kept outside, especially in a pen. He loves to be indoors with his people and he is house trained and crate trained! Dawson has put on some muscle since he has been in our foster home so he's a strong boy, but all heart. He tends to pull on a leash when he gets excited, so his adopter will need to be willing continue working on the training that we've started with him. 

Will you be a Hero in Dawson's story?

Visit our website/Click on Adopt to APPLY today!  RARErescue.org

Adoption Fee: $185.00



Please REMEMBER, All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption



PLEASE NOTE: We are a non-profit organization without municipal or government funding. Veterinary/Medical expenses are constant for an animal rescue. Our adoption fees not only help to provide vetting and care for the animal being adopted, but they also help to cover heartworm treatments and other treatable ailments that many animals, that would otherwise be euthanized, need in order to be made available for adoption.


Please understand that adopting an animal is a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to that animal and there will be veterinary expenses throughout their life that can often cost several hundreds, if not thousands of dollars (without pet insurance), especially without annual checkups and preventative care.  As a potential family for this pet you are responsible for their safety and that includes keeping them on your property.

***If you are not in the middle Tennessee area, transport can potentially be arranged to approved homes, depending on distance and local adaptability. We normally do not allow adoptions outside of 1.5 hours driving distance.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, foster, or aid in the rescue efforts of RARE!

Age:  as of 1.7.21, 8 months
Weight:  54 lbs.
Good with dogs:  yes
Good with cats:  unsure
Good with kids:  no kids under 8 yrs.
Energy level:  medium to high
Good with men/strangers:  yes
Hypoallergenic:  no

Special home requirements or medical:  needs a secure yard and another dog

Additional info:

Ozzy is a big happy puppy who gets the biggest wiggle butt when meeting new people! He loves attention and his person so does have some separation anxiety.  He is extremely playful and a very active pup that needs a secure yard to play in and would benefit from having another dog to play with or an active person that can work with him on basic training, socialization and give him regular long walks or runs. When playing, he can be mouthy and given his size he is very strong so it's best he not be in a home with little people, so no kids under the age of 8 years. Ozzy is a young very rambunctious boy and barks at noises that startles him so he should not be in a home with shared walls. When he gets proper exercise he does become calm and will chill at your feet for a good nap. He is still growing and can possibly grow to be around 80 lbs.

INTERESTED IN THIS PUP?  If you want to know if the puppy is still available- we advise you to go ahead and apply which will free us up to review your application.  We thank you for your patience.  Our inbox gets flooded with so many puppy requests it takes us longer to respond.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ THE DOG'S INFORMATION CAREFULLY.  ONCE YOU HAVE DONE SO, PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING:
1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.
4.       To learn more about our adoption process, please look up our Adoption FAQ’s. - http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-faq/

Say hello to Gordon! - an adorable 7 year old , 45 pound male pit mix - heavy on the mix !  
Gordon is a very easy going boy who has a healthy level of energy;  but happy to chew on a bone and take a nap after a nice walk . Gordon walks beautifully on a leash and knows his basic manners . Gordon is very affectionate and gives lots of kisses ! He would love to snuggle up on the couch with you for an afternoon nap or to watch a movie . We have been told he is diagnosed with a heart murmur and may need some medication in the future , but for now this boy is spunky and happy as can be ! This boy has truly won over our hearts here at the shelter - I’d be very surprised if you did not feel the same once meeting him - if interested please come visit Gordon.

animal.description:
Updated: 01/26/2021
Meet Jolene!!! She's about 3 years old, she was a skinny 45 lbs when she arrived from TX a few weeks ago, but has been in weight-gain mode and is filling out nicely. Jolene loves to have a warm body to cozy up to, she prefers the warm touch of her humans but will settle for the comfort of her foster sister dog as well. When you come home or simply come back into her view after a bit, she acts as though she hasn't seen you in years, she will always make you feel loved. She loves to play with her toys, especially tug of war. She is totally housebroken, she does her business like clockwork which makes for easy bathroom breaks in the cold weather. She enjoys car rides, especially if it involves a trip to the dog park or picking up her human foster sister and brother. Jolene can be as active or as content as you would like, she will join you on 5 mile runs, but will also settle next to you on the couch if you just don't have the energy that day. She has been a great office dog, my husband works from home, and he can conduct his business with very little distractions from her. She likes to wake up early to use the bathroom and eat breakfast but usually goes back to bed afterwards, she doesn't seem to be a morning dog. We crate her at night, during the day she has the run of our kitchen and family room while my husband is on the second floor. We have had little to no incidents of chewing on things that do not belong to her. Her most active time of the day is between 2:00 pm and 8:00 pm when everybody is home and ready for some playtime. She loves doing laps outside or chasing tennis balls. Inside, she likes soft or rubber chew toys. Oh, and NO CATS! She can't resist chasing and the cats aren't interested in waiting around to see what happens next.
She's a dog that loves her her doggy friends but adores her humans of all ages, she can't wait to start her forever life!
Adoption Fee: $475.00
We are a Wisconsin state licensed dog rescue -WI# 402433

***We do not have a central adoption center at this time. All our dogs are in private foster homes within WI. At this time we only place our dogs in areas of WI. The breed of our dogs is our best guess with the help of our veterinarians.
Our Weight Classes are as follows:
0- 25lbs - Small
26- 45lbs - Medium
46-89 - Large
90+ X-large
If you are adopting an adult dog, which we consider 6 months of age or older, your adoption fee includes the following:
Spay/Neuter, Rabies and Distemper shots, dewormed, flea & tick preventative, heartworm tested and microchipped.
If you are adopting a dog younger than 6 months of age, the dog will be up to date on the shots as per the dogs age. The dog will be dewormed, flea/tick preventative and microchipped. We only spay/neuter our dogs by 6 months of age. If you decide to adopt a younger dog than 6 months of age, they will need to be spayed/neutered at one of our preferred clinics. This will be determined by your contract along with the month they should have their surgery. This is included in your adoption fee.
Once you are approved with our rescue, you can meet any one of our dogs within the fosters home. If you are interested in the dog you met, you can take the dog home under our mandatory foster to adopt program. You receive 5 days to see if the dog is the right fit for your home.
If it is, we will conduct the home visit and finalize adoption. If it is not, it is returned to the foster. We are happy to find you another dog that meets your needs in your home.
If a dog is listed as PENDING, a family has met the dog and planning on adopting the dog after the home visit has been conducted. We always suggest sending in an application for a dog because there are times where the dogs are given back to us under the foster to adopt program. There are many reasons dogs are returned but normally it just was not the right fit for all.Please go to WWW.TAILWAGGERS911.COM under HOW TO ADOPT . We have an online application that is very easy to fill out.

animal.description:
Updated: 1/25/2021

Hi, I'm Bandit. I am about 6 years old and weigh about 45 lbs. Now, if you've clicked on my profile, then I'm guessing you know the challenges that Border Collies can be, so please give me a chance and keep reading!

I spent most of my life outside down in TX, and have been working hard to get used to life on the inside, and I'm proud to say I've done pretty well! I've still got a ways to go, though, so I'm not a first-time dog owner kind of guy. I've conquered stairs (those were scary), and I still keep an eye on that big screen TV! Every day I see something I haven't seen before, but will slowly learn that these things just aren't scary as long as there is someone there to guide me. So far, I've done best by following the other laid-back dog that lives here and listening to foster mom tell me "you got this!", that lets me know that none of this stuff will bother dogs! That means I *need* a confident doggy friend as I learn to navigate this whole new world, and a patient and dog-savvy family that will help build my confidence and understand my needs. But you can cross housetraining off my list - I have quickly figured out that *outdoors* is where dogs go to do their business then they can come back inside! I do love my crate, it's a safe spot for me to hide out, and I sleep in it through the night without a sound. I'm not protective of my food or treats, and am learning to take snacks gently. I quietly lie down and ignore you while you eat, and I won't steal your sandwich! I do have energy, but I am a bit older so it's not a crazy thing. We go for a 2-3 mile walk in the morning, and a 2 mile walk at night, and then I spend the rest of the day supervising my foster mom while she works. And on the weekends we get to go to the dog park, which I love! I'm not the best around really small dogs who are submissive in that setting, I can't resist the urge to herd them and that can freak them out. Oh, and I do the same to cats, which of course they hate! There's a big fenced in yard where I'm staying, so I can do laps and zoomies with the other dog as much as I want, but truly what I really want is to be by you as much as I can once I've had my fun. If I do encounter something outside I don't like, I will run - so I *need* that fenced in yard! I don't mind the cold at all and really love the snow, I roll around it in every time we go outside, but that's only if you're with me - if you head indoors, I'd rather come back in with you. I also ignore all those small furry things outside, like bunnies and squirrels and chipmunks, I'm just not interested in them. I'm learning how to play with toys, the ones with squeakers still freak me out, but I'm slowly picking my (quiet) favorites out of the toy chest and carrying them to my crate. Outside, my absolute favorite is herding a 5 gallon bucket around, it makes my foster mom laugh! I'm super friendly with new dogs, and I greet the people I meet in the neighborhood with a gentle tail wag and sweet butterfly kisses. I love quietly looking out the window on car rides, and you can touch my ears, paws, tail - I'm not touchy anywhere!

So here's the thing - my breed was bred to watch over my flock and bring them back by any means necessary, so no small children please. I don't need constant exercise, but I do need a family who understands my requirements - if I'm left to my own devices, I can develop my own little "quirks". Right now, I am scared of the random electronic beeps I hear in the house, and last week I decided that I was scared of the backyard. So even though I'm adorable, I need constant work to keep me mentally healthy! I know my basic commands like sit and lie down, and as I get more comfortable with my foster family, I'm learning to come when they call me, cause they always have a treat or a scratch to give me! I wouldn't do well in an apartment type setting which requires me to always be on leash. I'm really good on my leash, but I still need room to RUN, it's just what makes me happy. I'm also a quick learner, so maybe we could go for a good long run, or try agility, or search and rescue, or anything else that involves FUN with my people!

If you're looking for a smart, fun, affectionate boy, know all of the fun and challenges I will bring you, and have lots of patience, get your application in so we can meet and we can start our amazing life together!

Adoption Fee: $475.00

We are a Wisconsin state licensed dog rescue -WI# 402433

***We do not have a central adoption center at this time. All our dogs are in private foster homes within WI. At this time we only place our dogs in areas of WI. The breed of our dogs is our best guess with the help of our veterinarians.
Our Weight Classes are as follows:
0- 25lbs - Small
26- 45lbs - Medium
46-89 - Large
90+ X-large
If you are adopting an adult dog, which we consider 6 months of age or older, your adoption fee includes the following:
Spay/Neuter, Rabies and Distemper shots, dewormed, flea & tick preventative, heartworm tested and microchipped.
If you are adopting a dog younger than 6 months of age, the dog will be up to date on the shots as per the dogs age. The dog will be dewormed, flea/tick preventative and microchipped. We only spay/neuter our dogs by 6 months of age. If you decide to adopt a younger dog than 6 months of age, they will need to be spayed/neutered at one of our preferred clinics. This will be determined by your contract along with the month they should have their surgery. This is included in your adoption fee.
Once you are approved with our rescue, you can meet any one of our dogs within the fosters home. If you are interested in the dog you met, you can take the dog home under our mandatory foster to adopt program. You receive 5 days to see if the dog is the right fit for your home.
If it is, we will conduct the home visit and finalize adoption. If it is not, it is returned to the foster. We are happy to find you another dog that meets your needs in your home.
If a dog is listed as PENDING, a family has met the dog and planning on adopting the dog after the home visit has been conducted. We always suggest sending in an application for a dog because there are times where the dogs are given back to us under the foster to adopt program. There are many reasons dogs are returned but normally it just was not the right fit for all.Please go to WWW.TAILWAGGERS911.COM under HOW TO ADOPT . We have an online application that is very easy to fill out.

animal.description:
Hi there!  My name is TREVOR.  What’s yours?  Nice to meet ya!  

WATCH MY VIDEO:  https://youtu.be/1tXnnodjV3s

If you like me, ask my foster for a better video!

A nice person came along and took me in and, now, I am ready to hit the road to your house!  Uh, make that “our” house, OK?  I definitely need a house with a fenced-in yard cuz I need room to run and romp and be safe!  The rescue requires (1) a fenced-in yard and (2) a vet reference from a vet that you have used for a current or previous dog to be sure that all vetting was done.  

I am a Whippet/Terrier mix.  I am 8 MONTHS old and I weigh 25 pounds.  I will probably weight 35 - 40 pounds fully grown. I have been neutered and am up to date on vaccines so I'm ready to go to my new home with YOU!!  Those funny-looking 2-legged creatures said I’m also microchipped – whatever THAT is.  At any rate, I am fully vetted.  Is that anything close to petted?  I love to be petted!  They say I'm precious.  Hmmm, Is my name Trevor or Precious?

Wanna hear some more good stuff about me?  OK, here goes.  I like ALL people and ALL dogs.  I need to have a DOGGIE SIBLING so we can run and romp together and burn up LOTS and LOTS of energy!   If you don't have a doggie sibling, I need someone who can play with me and love on me a w-h-o-l-e lot!  How about all day and evening, every day?  OK?

I have lots to learn.  Will you teach me all the things a pup needs to know to be safe and happy? I LOVE to give kisses so get ready!  

If you have children, then need to be older children - 12 and up because I like to play hard and run fast!  It's fun!

Since I was rescued, I've learned to use a doggie door at my foster's home.  Smart, huh? I like to take naps when I'm tired from playing.  I need  love, exercise and couch-sitting when we get tired!  Let's be a team, OK?

If you would like to take me home (and you know you do), please email doggydarlings12@gmail.com  and they can get me on my way to a new and loving home!  Once you adopt me, I will be flown to Seattle from Houston, TX.  (That's the only place we can fly to right now.)  My adoption fee is $450 and includes my vetting, neutering, flight cost, travel crate, Health Certificate and a microchip.

animal.description:
LLOYD!!
GOOD with dogs, GOOD with kids, UNKNOWN with cats

Adoption Fee: $450

Hello world!! My name is Lloyd, and I am part of the construction trio that came to rescue. I came with my 2 brothers after we were found living in an abandoned house by some construction workers. No one is sure how long we were living there, but it is approximated by a vet that I am 10 months old, and I am all puppy! What does “all puppy” mean? I have been in rescue for a couple of weeks now, and I am learning everything about life, but I am going to need a patient person to love me while I learn. I have no manners, so you might need a hard hat to wear while you are teaching me about all the things that I need to learn so that you don’t hurt your head from the potential frustration that might come with this. Now, don’t get me wrong, because I am truly amazing, have the sweetest personality, absolutely LOVE people, and I love to play, but there is a lot that I am working on. These are the things that I am working on. I am still potty training, so I need a strict routine that will make sure that I continue learning how to go outside when I need to go. I will go in my kennel when I need to, but I am not a fan of it. I eventually settle down in there, but I want to be there the action is, so we’ve learned that being in my kennel in view of my family is what makes me settle faster. As you might imagine, I have had to learn to find food my entire young life, and so food for me is a great motivator, but it also means that I am very protective of my food because I am still learning that it will always be there, so for now, it is best that I am fed separately from any other dogs that might be in my new home. Due to food being a high value possession for me, bones and treats are something that I only get while in my kennel. It’s being used in a 2-fold manner in the sense that it’s making me realize that my kennel is a great place to be, but it’s also not creating a potential issue if there are other dogs in the home. Did I mention that I love to play? Oh boy! I have energy and love to run and play with my toys and people. I am not aggressive at all, but I am still learning when play time is over or when I need to settle because I am getting a little too excited. Well, there’s where I am in this great big world. I am learning so much, but I still have a ways to go. I know that I am cute and cuddly looking, but I want make sure that you know I am a work in progress. I will get there, but it will take some time, some love, and a whole lot of patience. Up for the challenge?? If so, head on over and fill out my application, and let’s get this party started! Hard hat potentially required, Lloyd. (UPDATED 12/09/20)

Goldie is 1 year old, 35lbs, looking for a home that’ll fit both her active and chill lifestyle. Goldie is a sweet girl that’ll need some work and in return, be your loyal companion.
 Put simply, Goldie is an introverted gal that can be overstimulated easily. Good news: her foster home knows a lot about her and all the ways to make her a happy pup that’s fun to live with.
 She is super smart and highly treat motivated. She enjoys learning new tricks. She does well with other dogs when given a controlled environment like hiking or walking with friends. When off leash, she gets too aroused and it’s a bit frustrating to other dogs. For this reason, Goldie is looking for a home without other dogs or cats, but would do fine with having dog friends on adventures.
 She loves playing fetch with stuffed toys and working on enrichment puzzles. She finds a lot of self soothing in sniffing and gnawing, so she does awesome with “find it” games outside, licky-mats, and sniffing out food in snuffle mats. She loves chewing on sticks, bully sticks, frozen bone marrow bones, and working on kongs as a nice night-time routine or chill-out activity.
 She’s crate trained, house trained, and knows a lot of tricks - sit, down, shake, etc. She is super smart and eager to learn more.
 Goldie is working on mouthiness when aroused while running in the backyard (already SO much better), counter surfing, and walking well on leash. For this reason, we are recommending kids 12yrs+ and a strong owner for her until she’s a bit more mature and trained.
 She takes 5 mins to settle in her crate at night and then is silent and keeps her crate clean, so we are looking for a living situation without shared walls. Goldie would benefit most from an adventure lifestyle, country living, agility training or a strong running buddy that can exercise her and then veg out at night. Goldie is looking for someone who understands that she’s an adolescent. After all her adventures, she benefits from a nice nook to decompress in. To help her decompress, she likes to take a chamomile + hemp edible, simmer in lavender, chew on a bone or sniff something out, and listen to relaxing music. Can you be that forever home she’s looking for?

Apply today at http://www.underdogpetrescue.org/dog-application

**Please note: Our animals live in foster homes throughout the Madison area. We do not have a shelter where animals are available for daily viewing. Applying is the first step in our process.**

Dogs from Underdog Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
Spay/Neuter
Rabies, Distemper, and Bordetella Vaccinations (as age appropriate-puppy adopters may need to cover some vaccine boosters)
Heartworm Test (for dogs over 6mo)
Microchip
Deworming
Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

Our adult dog adoption fee is $300. Our puppy (under 5 mo) is $375. Our senior dog (over 8 yrs) is $250.

*Please note that all breeds noted are estimates or best guesses. We very rarely have information on our animals' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays*
